INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (30, 7, 'Assignment: Read the curriculum of your own discipline, identify the strengths and weaknesses of it, state how to improve and how to implement the curriculum in your own situation.', '<p><u>MADAM, </u></p><p><u>SORRY, BECAUSE OF DIFFICULTY I FACED IN FIRST ATTEMPT AS ATTACHMENT, I AM RE SENDING AS COPY PASTE.</u></p><p><u>THANKS.</u></p><p><u>A.E.MD.ABDUL WASEY</u></p><p><br></p><p>DISCIPLINE:SURGERY AND ALLIED SUBJECTS</p><p><br></p><p>INTRODUCTION </p><p>Surgery is a major discipline of undergraduate medical education (MBBS) curriculum. Various aspects and specialties of Surgery are included in the “curriculum for undergraduate medical Education in Bangladesh--updated 2012”, approved by Bangladesh Medical and Dental Council (BM & DC). </p><p><br></p><p>STRENGTHS OF THE CURRICULUM</p><p>GOAL, AIMS &OBJECTIVES</p><p>At the beginning of main curriculum National goal and objectives of MBBS course, learning out comes/ competences of fresh graduates are described comprehensively. These descriptions of goal, objectives are equally applicable to all clinical subjects including surgery and allied subjects. These descriptions give a clear idea to teachers, students and other stake holders, of the need, goal, purpose, objectives and competences of our medical graduates who will undergo successfully through this curriculum to become a graduate (MBBS) doctor. The curriculum is based on traditional method in sequential manner, not integrated.</p><p>Curriculum of surgery is discipline based. Departmental objectives of surgery department are out lined at the beginning of surgery and Allied Subjects chapter of the curriculum. In departmental objectives of surgery discipline the aim of leaning surgery on the basis of need is outlined. A list of competences/abilities to perform certain tasks (physical, verbal, communication, thinking, manipulative) is short listed under the headings of clinical, communication, Managerial and Manipulative and Practical skills.</p><p>Departmental objectives are good guidelines for teachers and concerned persons to conduct the teaching – learning programme to students with a definite aim.   </p><p>A guideline of teaching learning methods, teaching aids, in course (formative) assessment procedures are mentioned in tabular from. Equipments and appliances necessary to demonstrate and teach the students surgery and allied subjects are comprehensively listed, which is of great help to the department to collect and keep the things ready for demonstration. </p><p>Course contents and learning objectives are given in details. Course contents are divided in to different systems of surgery and allied subjects .Contents are divided in to core and additional according to priority of learning objectives. Contents are distributed at various phases (year) of study in stepwise from basic to advanced. Duration/ time is allocated for different topics of course contents, which help the department and the concerned teachers to plan the lessons (lesson-plan). In learning objectives against each system or topic, what a student should be able to know, state, perform, are mentioned clearly. This part of curriculum is of great help to student to know, what to learn, and to teachers what and how to teach.</p><p>CONTENTS AND FORMATIVE ASSESSMENT</p><p>Class performance record cards are prescribed for clinical (bed-side teaching), practical and tutorial teaching-learning .Under each heading several relevant topics are listed in the card for teaching learning.</p><p>Different cards are to be learned in different phases (year) of study from basic to advance level of learning. After teaching and learning a topic there is assessment/evaluation, the result of which is noted in a box against the name of the topic. On completion/end of the card it is easily can be seen whether all the topics are covered and the overall performance of the student. There is provision for final/card completion examination and to note down the result in the card, with attendance of the student. This is as established and well coordinated method of formative assessment.</p><p><br></p><p>Though the curriculum is not based on integrated method, but integrated teaching is included only for few common topics. Topics of integrated teaching are listed and instructed to schedule once in a month involving as many as possible specialties. This type of teaching definitely increases the interest of student in learning the subject.</p><p>A mixed educational strategies are adopted in this curriculum.</p><p>A summary in tabular form of the duration of lectures demonstrations, tutorials, clinical/ bed side teaching in  various phases (year of study period) of various specialties of surgery and allied along with time allotted for block posting, formative exam and summative exam is given for at a glance review of the whole curriculum which helps the department to prepare an academic calendar.</p><p>SUMMATIVE ASSESSMENT METHODS AND PROCEDURES</p><p>At the end of the curriculum, different aspects and methods of summative assessment (final professional examination) of surgery are outlined. Assessment is an essential part of curriculum, without mentioning the assessment method a curriculum remains incomplete. The results of assessment in terms of different grades of marks are well mentioned.  How the assessment is performed both teacher and student should know thoroughly. In this chapter it is well described. </p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p>WEAKNESS OF THE CURRICULUM</p><p>This curriculum is based on traditional method and discipline based.  In classical traditional method students start learning surgery after finishing the learning of subjects of basic science(anatomy, physiology, biochemistry) and applied science (pathology, microbiology, pharmacology). But in this curriculum students start learning clinical subjects like surgery and medicine after finishing the course of anatomy, physiology and biochemistry in Phase -II. Pathology, microbiology and Pharmacology are taught in phase-III one year after starting the clinical subjects. Without a basic knowledge of these subjects teaching – learning of surgery is difficult. In Phase –II forensic medicine and community medicine are included, to learn these subjects knowledge of  pathology, microbiology and pharmacology is also essential. In this curriculum sequence of learning is not well maintained.</p><p>Topics mentioned in surgery curriculum is wide open and no limitation of knowledge is demarcated, as result the teachers may not be able to limit their knowledge dissemination, and information overload occurs frequently. So topics should be made more specified regarding the limit and depth of knowledge.</p><p>In the curriculum there are some discrepancies in teaching hours. </p><p><br></p><p>To improve and implement the curriculum of surgery at the institutional level, the following points are to be considered actively:</p><p><br></p><p>1.<span xss=removed> </span>All the teachers of the surgery and allied subjects should have knowledge about the curriculum, particularly regarding related subject of the concerned teacher. To disseminate the knowledge of the curriculum and an action plan to set, a departmental workshop can be arranged at the beginning of each session. </p><p>2.<span xss=removed> </span>To follow the quality assurance scheme designed by Centre for Medical Education is a prescribed way to monitor the curriculum implementation in an institute.  </p><p><br></p><p>COMMUNICATIONS OF CURRICULUM</p><p>3.<span xss=removed> </span>Students should be well informed regarding the curriculum in brief including formative and summative assessment methods and procedures, so that they can participate and contribute by periodical feedback of the progress and any difficulty they face.</p><p>4.<span xss=removed> </span>An academic calendar of the department for each batch/session of students should be prepared well ahead of starting the class.</p><p>5.<span xss=removed> </span>A study guide with a list of learning resources and list of standard text books suggested by faculty members should be handed over to students for study at the beginning of session.</p><p><br></p><p>TEACHING METHODS</p><p>6.<span xss=removed> </span>Lectures are to be interactive.</p><p>7.<span xss=removed> </span>A lesson plan for lecture class to be prepared with an idea to avoid information overload.</p><p>8.<span xss=removed> </span>Small group teachings are to be included in the class routine for more interactive discussion.</p><p>9.<span xss=removed> </span>Integrated teaching is to be arranged as per schedule and on the topic prescribed in the curriculum.</p><p>10.<span xss=removed> </span> Pathology, Microbiology and Pharmacology are not included in Phase –II, but clinical subject surgery classes start in Phase-II. It is difficult to continue teaching –learning programme of surgery without some basic knowledge of Pathology, Microbiology and Pharmacology. So arrangement should be made for some classes of the mentioned subjects in class routine of Phase-II, in consultation with heads of the mentioned department of the subjects to facilitate the teaching –learning programme.</p><p><br></p><p>ASSESSMENT</p><p>11.<span xss=removed> </span>Prescribed periodic formative assessment should be arranged and conducted as per schedule, and the results are to be announced for feedback of performance of students and as well as evaluation of teaching performance.</p><p>12.<span xss=removed> </span>A rehearsal of summative assessment should be arranged to familiar the students with the methods of  summative assessment at the end of the course.</p><p><br></p><p>REVIEW AND FEEDBACK</p><p>13.<span xss=removed> </span>All the teachers of the department should meet once in a month on a fixed date to discuss the progress, problems, and find out the solution and any correction in schedule.</p><p>14.<span xss=removed> </span>Members of the faculty will provide in writing the difficulties or deficiencies they face during conducting the course in curriculum to head of the faculty time to time. Head of the faculty will compile them and report it to appropriate authority or present in forums of national curriculum development.</p><p>A.E.MD.ABDUL WASEY</p><div><br></div>', '2018-01-23 06:28:57', NULL, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Positive:<o></o></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Timely submitted<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Properly submitted<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The introduction with the statement of basic understanding\r\nabout the curriculum is appropriately written.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Most of the components of a curriculum is touched.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Challenges:<o></o></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Volume:  Expected in 800\r\nwords. Written 1400 words.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The expected changes in the participants are one of the way\r\nto chalk out the content of curriculum.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A conclusion could be added to the text you have written.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Evaluation of the curriculum should be done by students as\r\nwell.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">More teaching staff / more teachers skilled in teaching\r\nmethodology are needed.<o></o></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">There are many constrains at the institution level, teachers\r\ncommitment , facilities available , students motivation in implementing the\r\ncurriculum in my institution.<o></o></p>', NULL, '2018-01-23 18:28:57', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (31, 15, 'Assignment: Evaluation of our MBBS curriculum on Anatomy. Identification of its strengths and weaknesses. Suggestions how to improve and implement the curriculum.', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>Strengths :<o></o></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>1. Well organised.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>2. Structured.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>3. Systematic delivery of content by the teaching stuff.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>4. Specific content.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>4. Specific aims and objectives to acheive the goal.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>5. Outcome base education.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>6. Formative assesment.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>7.Summative assesment.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>7. Comprehensive<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>8. Multiple choice question (MCQ)  in written examination.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>9.  Short answered\r\nquestion (SAQ) instead of long question in written examination.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>10.Inclusion of radiology and imaging oriented anatomy study\r\nand assesment. <o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>11.Inclusion of surface anatomy oriented anatomy study and  assesment.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>12. Inclusion of OSPE in practical examination.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>13. Proper sequence of implementation to obtain the aims and\r\nobjectives<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>14. Series of planned activies for specific learning outcome.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>15.Constant monitoing, examination (item,card and term),\r\nevaluation, assesment by the teaching staff.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>16. Small group teaching making the curriculum both student\r\nand teacher centered.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>17. Specifying the curriculum into core content and learning\r\nobjectives. <o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>17. well ordered in delivery of component for better learning\r\noutcome.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>18. lecture integrated teaching.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>19. Inclusion of tutorial, practical and demonstration\r\noriented teaching method.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><o> </o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>Weaknesses:<o></o></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>1. In multiple choice question (MCQ) making core curriculum\r\npartially followed.<b><o></o></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>2. Questions repeat while preparing multiple choice question\r\nand short answered question. <o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>2. Partially integrated.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>3. Allocated time in order to content is not enough.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>4. Overloaded with examination in order to allocated time.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>5. Relatively less emphasis on clinical oriented anatomy\r\nstudy and assesment.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>6. Clinical part of any Anatomy topic teaching not practical\r\noriented.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>7. Teaching part is not integrated among Anatomy, Physiology\r\nand Biochemistry <o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>8. No specific standard, allocation of resources.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>9. No specific standard about educational environment.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>10. Not task oriented.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>11. More teacher centered.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>12. Inclusion of some contents which are usually regarded to\r\nbe of higher level of difficulty e.g . some topic of genetics and nervous\r\nsystem.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><o> </o></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>Suggestion  For \r\nImprovement :<o></o></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>1.Task based and problem based teaching should be practiced\r\nmore.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>2. Integrated teaching should be more practiced among\r\nanatomy, physiology and biochemistry.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>3. Resources should be adressed specifically.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>4. Oral examination should be more structured and  more flexible in order to interact with the\r\nexaminee to facilate her response.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>5. Core content should be more specific in the field of hard\r\ncore, soft core and optional core content.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>6. Time allocation for radiology imaging a