INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (44, 38, 'Importance of Taxonomy and Learning Objective in educational program', 'Importance of Taxonomy & Learning Objective in educational program- \r\n\r\nLearning means change of behavior or capacity to new behavior. Our aim is to indicate clearly the intent of our instruction in terms of the type of behavior that our student is expected to show. Good learning objectives are actual outcomes and not simply activities students will complete or things we will do as an instructor. Good learning objectives are clear, concise, and specific statements describing a student’s behaviors. Good learning objectives are consistent with the goals of the course/curriculum & realistic and doable for the learner’s level. Student learning objectives serve as a guide to the curriculum for both students and faculty.  Learning objectives relate to the cognitive level of the course content as well as the teaching modalities and assessment activities used in a module. \r\n It is often quite difficult to relate inputs to outcomes in the world of education. Traditionally, much work has been done to develop and provide inputs into the process of education. But rarely has one been able to measure or predict the learning outcomes from using these inputs.\r\nIf we are going to really understand how we might be impacting student learning we must do two things. First we must define our student learning outcomes – these are the goals that describe how a student will be different because of a learning experience. The focus should be on what a student will be able to do with the information or experience. And second, we must measure if the program or service implemented to facilitate the learning was effective.\r\nIt may be difficult to know where to start in writing a student learning outcome. Learning taxonomies are a valuable tool for classifying learning objectives. A helpful and frequently used resource when writing student learning outcomes is Bloom’s Taxonomy of Cognitive Skills. Bloom’s Taxonomy refers to a classification of the different objectives that educators set for students (learning objectives). The taxonomy was first presented in 1956 through the publication “The Taxonomy of Educational Objectives, The Classification of Educational Goals, Handbook I: Cognitive Domain” (Bloom 1956). It is considered to be a foundational and essential element within the education community as evidenced in the 1981 survey “Significant writings that have influenced the curriculum: 1906-1981” (Shane 1981).\r\nImportance of Educational objectives is in the development of successful learning experiences for our students and in our own development as an educator. \r\nMore specifically, learning objectives-\r\n• Force us to look again.  The exercise of writing or rewriting objectives prompts us to examine content we may have been teaching in much the way for years, but with a new perspective.\r\n• Help us trim the fat.  Allowing our learning objectives to drive our content or activity can result in discovering extraneous content that may be trimmed or an activity that doesn’t quite hit the target and needs tweaking.  We may simply be inspired to reorganize a meandering PowerPoint with our learning objectives as an outline.\r\n• Can make our session “fall in line”.  Once written, learning objectives can confirm a solid alignment or organization of learning activities and assessments or suggest that a fresh pass at our design of the learning experience is needed.  \r\n• Can provide opportunities to present a more rich and challenging learning experience for our students. Our learning objectives will illuminate the order, whether higher or lower, to which we are asking our students to think, process, and learn during our session.\r\n• Be a guide for our students.  When displayed to students, learning objectives set student expectations, guide their learning processes, and help them focus their study time for the upcoming exam(s).\r\n5 specific objectives for the topic “Schizophrenia” according to the hierarchies in each learning domain-\r\nAfter completion of the course the student will be able to-\r\nCognitive domain-\r\n• Knowledge\r\nDefine schizophrenia according to DSM 5\r\n• Comprehension\r\nPredict the prognosis of schizophrenia in a particular case\r\n• Application\r\nDemonstrate psychotic symptoms in a case of schizophrenia\r\n• Analysis\r\nMake a differential diagnosis of psychotic symptoms\r\n• Synthesis\r\nMake a diagnosis of schizophrenia from a specific given case scenario\r\n\r\nPsychomotor domain-\r\n1. Perception\r\nDescribe the general appearance of a schizophrenic patient\r\n2. Guided response\r\nProvide psychoeducation to the parents of schizophrenic patient under supervision \r\n3. Mechanism\r\nConduct General Examination & MSE of a schizophrenic patient in role play\r\n4. Adaptations\r\nConduct MSE of an aggressive schizophrenic patient in role play\r\n5. Organization\r\nManage an aggressive schizophrenic patient in role play\r\nAffective domain\r\n1. Receiving\r\nBe aware of depressive symptoms in a post schizophrenic patient\r\n2. Responding\r\nAnswer the queries of parents of schizophrenic patients with empathy\r\n3. Valuing\r\nProvide supportive psychotherapy\r\n4. Organization\r\nJudge the need of psychosocial support for schizophrenic patient\r\n5. Characterization by a value complex\r\nChange the behavioral pattern according to level of insight of a schizophrenic patient.\r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n• https://medicaleducation.weill.cornell.edu/medical-education/instructional-design-services/importance-learning-objectives\r\n• https://med.ucf.edu/media/2011/08/writing_learning_objectives1.pdf \r\n• https://www.pearsoned.com/using-blooms-taxonomy-to-write-learning-outcomes/ \r\n• John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n• Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition\r\n', '2018-01-25 07:54:01', 'upload/attachment/1a77663ab2ecfaec2db45cbd564c1f3d.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (45, 43, 'Importance of Taxonomy and Learning Objective in educational program', 'Importance of Taxonomy & Learning Objective in educational program- \r\n\r\nLearning means change of behavior or capacity to new behavior. Our aim is to indicate clearly the intent of our instruction in terms of the type of behavior that our student is expected to show. Good learning objectives are actual outcomes and not simply activities students will complete or things we will do as an instructor. Good learning objectives are clear, concise, and specific statements describing a student’s behaviors. Good learning objectives are consistent with the goals of the course/curriculum & realistic and doable for the learner’s level. Student learning objectives serve as a guide to the curriculum for both students and faculty.  Learning objectives relate to the cognitive level of the course content as well as the teaching modalities and assessment activities used in a module. \r\n It is often quite difficult to relate inputs to outcomes in the world of education. Traditionally, much work has been done to develop and provide inputs into the process of education. But rarely has one been able to measure or predict the learning outcomes from using these inputs.\r\nIf we are going to really understand how we might be impacting student learning we must do two things. First we must define our student learning outcomes – these are the goals that describe how a student will be different because of a learning experience. The focus should be on what a student will be able to do with the information or experience. And second, we must measure if the program or service implemented to facilitate the learning was effective.\r\nIt may be difficult to know where to start in writing a student learning outcome. Learning taxonomies are a valuable tool for classifying learning objectives. A helpful and frequently used resource when writing student learning outcomes is Bloom’s Taxonomy of Cognitive Skills. Bloom’s Taxonomy refers to a classification of the different objectives that educators set for students (learning objectives). The taxonomy was first presented in 1956 through the publication “The Taxonomy of Educational Objectives, The Classification of Educational Goals, Handbook I: Cognitive Domain” (Bloom 1956). It is considered to be a foundational and essential element within the education community as evidenced in the 1981 survey “Significant writings that have influenced the curriculum: 1906-1981” (Shane 1981).\r\nImportance of Educational objectives is in the development of successful learning experiences for our students and in our own development as an educator. \r\nMore specifically, learning objectives-\r\n• Force us to look again.  The exercise of writing or rewriting objectives prompts us to examine content we may have been teaching in much the way for years, but with a new perspective.\r\n• Help us trim the fat.  Allowing our learning objectives to drive our content or activity can result in discovering extraneous content that may be trimmed or an activity that doesn’t quite hit the target and needs tweaking.  We may simply be inspired to reorganize a meandering PowerPoint with our learning objectives as an outline.\r\n• Can make our session “fall in line”.  Once written, learning objectives can confirm a solid alignment or organization of learning activities and assessments or suggest that a fresh pass at our design of the learning experience is needed.  \r\n• Can provide opportunities to present a more rich and challenging learning experience for our students. Our learning objectives will illuminate the order, whether higher or lower, to which we are asking our students to think, process, and learn during our session.\r\n• Be a guide for our students.  When displayed to students, learning objectives set student expectations, guide their learning processes, and help them focus their study time for the upcoming exam(s).\r\n5 specific objectives for the topic “Schizophrenia” according to the hierarchies in each learning domain-\r\nAfter completion of the course the student will be able to-\r\nCognitive domain-\r\n• Knowledge\r\nDefine schizophrenia according to DSM 5\r\n• Comprehension\r\nPredict the prognosis of schizophrenia in a particular case\r\n• Application\r\nDemonstrate psychotic symptoms in a case of schizophrenia\r\n• Analysis\r\nMake a differential diagnosis of psychotic symptoms\r\n• Synthesis\r\nMake a diagnosis of schizophrenia from a specific given case scenario\r\n\r\nPsychomotor domain-\r\n1. Perception\r\nDescribe the general appearance of a schizophrenic patient\r\n2. Guided response\r\nProvide psychoeducation to the parents of schizophrenic patient under supervision \r\n3. Mechanism\r\nConduct General Examination & MSE of a schizophrenic patient in role play\r\n4. Adaptations\r\nConduct MSE of an aggressive schizophrenic patient in role play\r\n5. Organization\r\nManage an aggressive schizophrenic patient in role play\r\nAffective domain\r\n1. Receiving\r\nBe aware of depressive symptoms in a post schizophrenic patient\r\n2. Responding\r\nAnswer the queries of parents of schizophrenic patients with empathy\r\n3. Valuing\r\nProvide supportive psychotherapy\r\n4. Organization\r\nJudge the need of psychosocial support for schizophrenic patient\r\n5. Characterization by a value complex\r\nChange the behavioral pattern according to level of insight of a schizophrenic patient.\r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n• https://medicaleducation.weill.cornell.edu/medical-education/instructional-design-services/importance-learning-objectives\r\n• https://med.ucf.edu/media/2011/08/writing_learning_objectives1.pdf \r\n• https://www.pearsoned.com/using-blooms-taxonomy-to-write-learning-outcomes/ \r\n• John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\nTahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition\r\n', '2018-01-25 07:55:06', 'upload/attachment/7580596e749ef341fd817e191736cc61.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (46, 32, 'importance of taxonomy & learning objective in educational program', 'Importance of taxonomy and learning objective:\r\nEducation is the process involving to facilitate learning, the chief goal of which is to bring about change in the behavior.  The sort of behavioral changes that the school attempts to bring about constitute the educational objectives.  Taxonomies of learning are the hierarchical classification in the field of education, have been developed by various groups concern with educational problems to help teachers to formulate precisely the educational objective. Taxonomy guides in grouping of objectives into types of learning capabilities utilized to plan the conditions required for successful learning, to determine the sequence of a segment of course to formulate instructional design and evaluation system.  The taxonomy guides all about in an educational program.  The important taxonomy are Bloom\'s Taxonomy, SOLO Taxonomy (Structure of Observed Learning Outcome) and McGuire preparation for achievement test. Educational psychologist consider three working levels of taxonomy to satisfy the need of evaluation.  The framework elaborated by Bloom and his colleague consist of six major categories: Knowledge, Comprehension, Application, Analysis, Synthesis, and Evaluation. Bloom classifies educational objectives into three domains, namely:\r\n1. The cognitive or mental skills (Knowledge) domain.\r\n2. The Affective or emotional (Attitude) domain.\r\n3. The psychomotor or physical skills domain.\r\nThe cognitive domain:\r\nThe cognitive domain refers to categories related to knowledge, comprehension, and critical thinking of a particular topic. Bloom classified these categories into six levels, moving through the lowest order processes to the highest:\r\ni. Knowledge\r\nRecalling facts, terms, basic concepts and answers. \r\nVerbs: arrange, define, duplicate, label, list, memorize, name, order, recognize, relate, recall, repeat, reproduce, state.\r\nii. Comprehension\r\nDemonstrative understanding of facts and ideas by organizing, comparing, translating, interpreting, giving descriptions, and stating main ideas. \r\nVerbs: classify, describe, discuss, explain, express, identify, indicate, locate, recognize, report, restate, review, select, translate.\r\niii. Application\r\nUsing new knowledge. Applying acquired knowledge, facts, techniques and rules in a different way.\r\nVerbs: apply, choose, demonstrate, dramatize, employ, illustrate, interpret, operate, practice, schedule, sketch, solve, use, write.\r\niv. Analysis\r\nExamine and break information into parts.\r\nVerbs: analyze, appraise, calculate, categorize, compare, contrast, criticize, differentiate, discriminate, distinguish, examine, experiment, question, test.\r\nv. Synthesis\r\nAssemble information together in a different way by combining elements in a new pattern or proposing alternative solutions.\r\nVerbs: arrange, assemble, collect, compose, construct, create, design, develop, formulate, manage, organize, plan, prepare, propose, set up, write.\r\nvi. Evaluation\r\nAssessing value, making judgments about information, validity of ideas or quality of work.\r\nVerbs: appraise, argue, assess, attach, choose compare, defend estimate, judge, predict, rate, core, select, support, value, evaluate.\r\nThe Affective domain:\r\nThe target in the affective domain is awareness and growth in attitudes, emotion, and feelings – emotional reaction and ability to feel another living thing’s pain or joy. Five levels are identified in the affective domain moving through the lowest order processes to the highest:\r\ni.Receiving\r\nThe lowest level; the student passively pays attention. Without this level no learning can occur.\r\nii.Responding\r\nNot only does the student attend the learning process but also responds and participates in some way.\r\niii.Valuing\r\nSeeing worth in new information\r\niv.Organizing\r\nFitting the new information into existing schema and deciding how the new information makes sense for you\r\nv.Characterizing\r\nMaking the new information part of your schema and exhibiting new behavior, attitude or belief\r\nThe Psychomotor domain:\r\nThe Psychomotor Domain is skill based and refers to the learning of skills. Physical skills are the ability to move, act, or manually manipulate the body to perform a physical movement. There are  three levels in the psychomotor domain according to RH Dave (1967)\r\nImportance of taxonomy include the following:\r\ni. Bloom’s taxonomy provides a universally effective strategy for creating all type of content to impart learning.\r\nii. The taxonomy helps teachers make decisions about the classification of content.\r\niii. Taxonomy also helps teachers map content to tasks that students need to perform.\r\niv. Taxonomy guides teachers to develop higher levels of thinking process for critical thinking or creative thinking.\r\nv. Using the taxonomy a teacher develops questions or projects that require the development of thinking and reflection from the knowledge level to the evaluation level.\r\nvi. A teacher or a syllabus designer designs a curriculum as well as classroom assignment using taxonomy to advance the learning process from recalling learning materials to higher level of thinking.\r\nvii. A teacher creates class activities based on Taxonomy.\r\nImportance of learning objective include the following:\r\nI. It provides directions to the instructor and it clearly conveys his instructional intent to others.\r\nII. It provides a guide for selecting the subject matter, the teaching method and the materials to be used during instruction.\r\nIII. It provides a guide for constructing tests and other instruments for evaluating student achievement.\r\nIV. If the expected learning outcomes are conveyed to the students, these outcomes also serve as a guide for the students learning activities.\r\n\r\nSpecific objectives on  “study of tumour” according to the hierarchies in each learning domain:\r\n1. KNOWLEDGE: Define and classify tumour.\r\n2. COMPREHENSION: Compare between benign and malignant tumour.\r\n3. APPLICATION: Which type of tumour is harmful for the body?.\r\n4. ANALYSIS: List four causes why the malignant tumours are harmful for the body. \r\n5. SYNTHESIS: Explain the benefits of benign tumour over malignant tumour by method or routs of metastasis.\r\n6. EVALUATION: Do you feel that early diagnosis of tumour can reduce the morbidity and mortality?.\r\n', '2018-01-28 12:11:59', 'upload/attachment/32c909ba0f848a871b76b905dadf8635.docx', '<p>You need to write 3 hierarchies in each learning domain and 5 learning capabilities that human can learn. Pl send me your response as early as possible<br></p>', NULL, '2018-01-29 00:11:59', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (47, 49, 'Describe the importance of taxonomy & learning objective in educational program. Write at least 5 specific objectives on any topic of your speciality according to the hierarchies in each learning domain.', 'Importance of taxonomy in educational program:\r\n1. Indicates the type of learning outcomes that should be considered.\r\n2. Provides a framework for classifying those outcomes.\r\n3. It is the backbone of many teaching philosophies, in particular, those that lean more towards     \r\n       skills rather than content.\r\n4. Forms the blueprint for forming the assessment tools.\r\n5. Provides common grounds & makes comparison of various teaching programs easier.\r\n6. Directs attention towards changes in student performance in a variety of areas.\r\n  \r\n\r\n Importance of learning objective in educational program:\r\n1. It guides planning instruction / lesson – By developing learning objectives for a course we can more rationally sequence instruction, allot time to topics, assemble materials, prepare outlines and booklists etc.\r\n2. It serves as a guidelines for providing instruction.\r\n3. It guides for assessment & evaluation.\r\n4. It guides for curriculum planning.\r\n5. Facilitating evaluation -  Learning objectives can facilitate various evaluation activities, evaluating students, evaluating instruction.\r\n6. Aiding in communication with others – There is need to communicate learning objectives to others: between instructor & student, with other instructors.\r\n7. Improving instruction -  If we intend to improve instruction in a particular lesson or course, we usually begin with the learning objectives for that lesson or course.\r\n8. Producing new insights – The process of clarifying objectives may produce major changes in those who engage in the effort.\r\n9. It guides the selection of content.\r\n10. It helps in development of an instructional strategy.\r\n11. For development & selection of instructional materials.\r\n12. For construction of tests & other instruments for assessing & then evaluating student learning outcomes.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSpecific objectives on Ultrasound (USG) guided aspiration of pleural effusion (topic-Radiology & Imaging) according to the hierarchies in each learning domain:\r\n      \r\n      Cognitive domain – \r\n1. To define the pleural effusion (Remembering).\r\n2. To explain the mechanism of pleural effusion (Understanding).\r\n3. To demonstrate the amount of pleural effusion in USG & aspirate about 50 ml (Applying).\r\n4. To compare the right side / left side pleural effusion (Analyzing).\r\n5. To evaluate the pleural effusion in USG against consolidation / collapse (Evaluating).\r\n6. To summarize the absence of haematoma at site of aspiration, Amount of fluid taken within 10% of the amount required, not more than two attempts, not very painful to patients (Creating).\r\n\r\nPsychomotor domain –\r\n1. To identify the pleural effusion in sitting position of patient on examination bed (Perception).\r\n2. To proceeds by blood set needle, sitting beside the patient for USG guided pleural fluid aspiration (Set).\r\n3. To follow USG guided introduce the needle under the guidance of instructor (Guided response).\r\n4. To construct the aspiration of USG guided pleural fluid with confidence & proficiency (Mechanism).\r\n5. To build up efficiency of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration (Complex overt response).\r\n6. To alter the site of aspiration if there is any difficulty in collection of pleural fluid (Adaptations).\r\n7. To arrange a new method of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration in decubitus position (Organization).\r\n\r\nAffective domain –\r\n1. To be aware of the pain during procedure of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration (Receiving).\r\n2. To state the patient about little painful procedure of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration (Responding).\r\n3. To support the patient about the findings of pleural fluid & a sufficient commitment to promote it (Valuing).\r\n4. To formulate the patient & his family that ready to help them to get over it (Organization).\r\n5. To believe that integration of the value into a total philosophy in such a way that it becomes a predictable behavioral characteristic (Characterization by a value complex).\r\n', '2018-01-27 22:42:49', 'upload/attachment/92955f7cc0a56c17f4fec008950cf12a.docx', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span xss=removed>Dear fellow<o></o></span></p><p xss=removed><span xss=removed>Thanks for your much effort for preparing  assignment. My observation are as below .<o></o></span></p><ul><li xss=removed><font color=\"#333333\" face=\"Arial, sans-serif\"><span xss=removed>Firstly write the </span><span xss=removed>assignment</span><span xss=removed> no and your name & ID no; Also some introduction about the topic(Taxonomy & Learning objective)</span></font></li><ul><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Taxonomy usually help to classify learning objectives;setting learning experience and learning objectives are the basis for designing curriculum,content,evaluation.<o></o></span></li><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Every specific objectives should have at least two things- <b>Task</b>(which include <u>act/action verb</u>, <u>Content</u> & <u>Condition</u>)  and <b>criteria</b>. The verb \'Draw/ Perform/diagnose/prepare/show\' etc can use for psycho-motor domain; In affective domain whether the learner satisfy/encourage/take safety measure.<o></o></span></li></ul><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Please rewrite accordingly and submit today. you should also mention your name/ID no.<o></o></span></li></ul><p></p><ul><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Prof Md Shah Alam (MBBS,DTCD, MCPS, MMEd)</span></li><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Prof & Head, Forensic Medicine</span></li><li xss=removed><span xss=removed>Ibrahim Medical College</span></li></ul>', NULL, '2018-01-28 10:42:49', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (48, 30, 'Importance of objectives in education.', ' INTRODUCTION: The ward objective stands for  a thing that is aimed for, or some thing we plan to do or achieve. in educational perspective objective is the pivot of teaching methodology. starting teaching without an objective should go in vein. it is not the description of the content of the course. objective is the goals of course.\r\nit should be in written form, well constructed ,& meets the purpose of teaching. According to Davies it should encompass the feeling, acts, or think at the end of learning process. That means after a successful teaching process it will change the learners behavior.\r\nthis behavioral change can be seen , heard or measured.\r\n\r\nTypes of objectives:  General& Specific are the two broad category of classifying objectives.  general objectives are used to describe the relevant programme.  specific objectives are more narrow & precise.\r\n\r\nImportance of objectives:  \r\na) It provides basic guidance for selection of the contents and procedures.\r\nb) It helps in evaluation of the success of instructions.\r\nc) It helps to attain the intent of instructions\r\n\r\nConclusions:  one good objectives does not require much more interpretation, or imagination. it should be specific, measurable, attainable, relevant & transferable.\r\n ', '2018-01-26 09:17:35', 'upload/attachment/789b9370d8dad83fc702d044857e796d.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
