INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (93, 63, 'Plan to improve educational environment and staff development program of Psychiatry Department BIRDEM & IMC', 'Learning environments are educational approaches, cultures, and physical settings for all types of learners and activities. Several of the key trends in educational models throughout the 20th and early 21st century include progressive education, constructivist education, and 21st century skills-based education. These can be provided in comprehensive or specialized schools in a variety of organizational models, including departmental, integrative, project-based, academy, small learning communities, and school-within-a-school. Each of these can also be paired, at least in part, with design-based, virtual school, flipped classroom, and blended learning models. We can apply these to our medical set up as well. We believe that the learning environment for medical education shapes the patient care environment. The highest quality of safe and effective care for patients and the highest quality of effective and appropriate education are rooted in human dignity. We embrace our responsibility to create, support, and facilitate the learning environment shared by our patients, learners, and teachers. In this environment, our patients witness, experience, and expect a pervasive sense of respect, collegiality, kindness, and cooperation among health care team members. This includes all professionals, administrators, staff, and beginning and advanced learners from all health professions. This includes research as well as patient care environments. We affirm our responsibility to create, support, and facilitate a learning environment that fosters resilience in all participants. It is our responsibility to create an atmosphere in which our learners and teachers are willing to engage with learning processes that can be inherently uncomfortable and challenging. We affirm our commitment to shaping a culture of teaching and learning that is rooted in respect for all. Fostering resilience, excellence, compassion, and integrity allows us to create patient care, research, and learning environments that are built upon constructive collaboration, mutual respect, and human dignity \r\nIn Bangladesh mental health expenditures from government health department are very insignificant and are less than 0.5%. In terms of affordability of mental health services less than 0.11% of the population has free access to essential psychotropic medication. The total number of human resources working in mental health facilities or private practice per 100,000 populations is 0.49 as stated in WHO-AIMS, 2005 report.  We have Stigma in the society, less awareness about mental health and inadequate manpower. However we have to try and overcome this adverse situation & we can only do it by improving the educational environment and proper staff development.\r\nTeachers, in their role in the learning environment, must teach to support and actively incorporate elements of motivation. We must ensure that when using innovative and fun teaching strategies, we embed elements that motivate our learners to do better. \r\nPlan to Improve Educational Environment and staff development program for the Department of Psychiatry, BIRDEM & IMC-\r\nLearning depends on several factors, but a crucial step is the engagement of the learner. This is affected by their motivation and perception of relevance. These, in turn, can be affected by learners\' previous experiences and preferred learning styles and by the context and environment in which the learning is taking place. In adult learning theories, teaching is as much about setting the context or climate for learning as it is about imparting knowledge or sharing expertise.  \r\nRegarding learning environment of my specialty I want to arrange role play and visit in community and tertiary care hospital which will motivate them for learning psychiatry by reducing stigma and negative attitude. I want to provide online self-assessment questioners for my students which will also motivate their learning. With the help of organization a Virtual learning environment can be created including online tools, databases and managed resources. Students can watch videos of rare and difficult cases which are not commonly presented in our Institute. Teaching and supporting staff is not sufficient for our specialty at present. We need to recruit more teachers and supporting staff for better service to our students.\r\nRegarding Staff development of our specialty teaching improvement is an important aspect. As our department lacks a good number of teachers we should implement self-directed learning by self-reflection & evaluation by students. Videotaping and supportive critiquing through online service from other departments or peer institute can be effective. We can involve students in different community level study through which our skills in conducting scientific study will improve as well. As we know “To teach is to learn twice” principle should be the main motivating factors for staff development.  Staff development programmes should base themselves on the needs of the individuals as well as the institution. Student needs, patient needs and societal needs may help to direct relevant activities. Assessing need is necessary to refine goals, determine content, identify preferred learning formats and assure relevance. So application of written questionnaires or surveys, interviews or focus group with key informants, observation of teachers’ in action’ & literature review  is a must for proper planning to be started for staff development in our institute.\r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Learning_environment\r\n2. WHO-AIMS Report on Mental Health System in Bangladesh, 2007.\r\n3. O’Sullivan PS. What’s in a learning environment? Recognizing teachers’ roles in shaping a learning environment to support competency. Perspect Med Educ (2015) 4:277–279.\r\n3. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n4. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education; 2013. First edition.\r\n', '2018-02-01 02:21:37', 'upload/attachment/e290975dafbd8c13fd07b8c30fd2f7ff.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (94, 66, 'Title: write a plan to improve educational environment and how to improve staff development program of your own department.', 'Submitted by-\r\nShudhanshu kumar saha\r\nEmail- shudhanshukumarsaha@gmail.com\r\nCell 01759961995\r\n\r\n                                      Educational environment\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nThe educational or learning environment can be defined in various ways. At its simplest it can mean the physical surroundings within which learning takes place, such as access to library facilities, seminar rooms or simulation equipment. However, references to the environment generally also encompass broader and less tangible notions of educational ‘climate’, ‘culture’ or ‘ethos’.\r\n In 2011 the Medical Education England (MEE) Medical Indicator Task and Finish Group went even further, writing that:  ‘An effective educational environment depends on the quality of the leadership, the quality of patient care, the nature of the infrastructure, and the preparation and support of trainers so that they are able to deliver their educational role.’\r\nThe American Medical Associatication (AMA) defined learning environment as ‘a social system that includes the learner (including the external relationships and other factors affecting the learner), the individuals with whom the learner interacts, the setting(s) and purpose(s) of the interaction, and the formal and informal rules/policies/norms governing the interaction.’ \r\nComponent:\r\nAMA goes on to describe it as comprising three broad components in any institution or setting: institutional culture, curriculum (both formal and informal) and good educational climate\r\nInstitutional culture: Individual faculty and institution used to decide what type of might be useful\r\nCourse and curriculum design: The designers of short and long courses should consider the relevance of the learning environment to the potential learners. The aims, objectives and assessment should be described. Teaching methods should build on learner’s experience.\r\nGood physical climate includes:\r\n• Adequate room size\r\n• Comfortable temperature\r\n• Avoid of distraction (noise, visual distraction inside or outside)\r\n• Seating arrangement should adequate\r\n• Audiovisual equipment should be available\r\nAll these factors of the environment that can affect concentration and motivation. Some are within teachers control, others not.\r\nMeasuring the educational environment:\r\nThe MEE Medical Indicators Task and Finish Group identified a range of indicators as the best measures for judging the quality of an educational environment. Survey tools, such as the Dundee Ready Education Environment Measure (DREEM), have been developed to enable ‘global readings and diagnostic analyses of undergraduate environments in medical schools and other health professions institutes’ \r\nDoes environment matter?\r\n If evidence of the effectiveness of a positive environment on learner outcomes is limited, the negative effects of an adverse climate seem to be well recognized. AMA, for example, refers to supervisors’ lack of professionalism during interactions with patients and trainees, pressure on learners to behave in ways they may perceive as unprofessional and the presence of harassment or bullying\r\nOn the other hand, the General medical council (GMC) 2011 State of Medical Education and Practice (SOMEP) report points to the effects of a positive environment. It notes research which ‘suggests that medical students and trainees gain from practical experience and positive role models’\r\nConclusion: So, improvement of these three environmental factors for the learning environment to the exclusion of other environmental considerations. Aside from population forecasts, community needs and relationship continue, for the most part to be ignored. The physical environment has been left to the architect and consulting engineers. Many building design solutions solved physical facility needs. Student representation on curriculum committees is one means of ensuring a more student centered course. Students who are having difficulties need to be identified early and given additional support\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                                  Staff development program\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\n Staff development/faculty development becomes an increasingly important component of medical education. Staff development activities have been designed to improve teacher effectiveness at all levels of educational continuum (e.g. undergraduate, postgraduate and continuing medical education) and diverse programmes have been offered to healthcare professionals in many settings. Bland et al 1990 defined staff development is a planned programme designed to prepare institutions and faculty members for their various roles\r\nObjective:\r\n1. There should be clearly defined the goals and priorities\r\n2. Target audience\r\n3. Choice of program, content and methodology\r\n\r\n  Faculty development functions include\r\n• Teaching skill\r\n• Understand the institutional/ organizational culture\r\n• Determine appropriate goals and priorities\r\n• Mentoring program\r\n•   Conduct needs assessments to ensure relevant programming\r\n• Develop different programs to accommodate diverse needs\r\n• Incorporate principles of adult learning and instructional design\r\n• Offer a diversity of educational methods\r\n• Prepare staff developers\r\n• Evaluate and demonstrate effectiveness \r\nOthers are\r\n• Decentralized activities\r\n• Peer coaching\r\n• Self-directed learning\r\n• Computer aided instruction\r\nEffective faculty development program: Effective programs focus on the participants, teachers, the program instructors, instructional methods and characteristics of the participants teaching setting\r\nEffective faculty development programs have the following characteristics\r\n• Address the needs of the faculty participants and institution\r\n• Takes into account the work palace of the teachers\r\n• Integrate curriculum that emphasizes theory and practice\r\n• Opportunity for practice and feedback\r\n• Build relationship among faculty members\r\n• Train more them one person from a setting\r\n\r\nBrief discussion of few methods\r\n\r\nTeaching skill: Teaching skill is key content of staff development programme. The aim is to improve teacher’s skill in clinical teaching, small group facilitation, lecturing, feedback and evaluation. Staff development has an important role to play in promoting teaching as a scholarly activity and in creating an educational leadership, innovation and excellence. \r\nUnderstand the institutional/ organizational culture: Staff development programmes take place within the context of a specific institution or organization. It is imperative to understand the culture of that institution and to be responsive to its needs. Staff development programmes should capitalize on the organization’s strength and work with the leadership to ensure success\r\nIncorporate principles of adult learning and instructional design: Adult come to learning situations with a variety of motivations and expectations about teaching methods and goals. Key principles of adult learning include the following\r\n• Adult are independent\r\n• Adult come to learning situations with a variety of motivations and definite   expectations about particular learning goals and teaching methods\r\n• Adult demonstrate different learning styles\r\n• Much of the adult learning is relearning rather than new learning\r\n• Adult learning often involves changes in attitudes as well as skills\r\n• Most adult prefer to learn through experience\r\n• Incentives for adult learning usually come from within the individual\r\n• Feedback is usually more important than tests and evaluations\r\n\r\nConclusion: Staff developers should be individuals who are well respected by their peers and have some educational expertise and experience in facilitating groups. “To teach is to learn twice “principle should be the main motivating factors for staff developer. To motivate faculty, we need to develop a culture that promote and encourage professional development, consider multiple approaches to achieving the same goal, tailor program to meet individual and organizational needs. Building a network of interested persons is integral to the faculty development program\r\n\r\nSubmitted by-\r\nShudhanshu kumar saha\r\nEmail- shudhanshukumarsaha@gmail.com\r\nCell 01759961995\r\n\r\n                                      Educational environment\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nThe educational or learning environment can be defined in various ways. At its simplest it can mean the physical surroundings within which learning takes place, such as access to library facilities, seminar rooms or simulation equipment. However, references to the environment generally also encompass broader and less tangible notions of educational ‘climate’, ‘culture’ or ‘ethos’.\r\n In 2011 the Medical Education England (MEE) Medical Indicator Task and Finish Group went even further, writing that:  ‘An effective educational environment depends on the quality of the leadership, the quality of patient care, the nature of the infrastructure, and the preparation and support of trainers so that they are able to deliver their educational role.’\r\nThe American Medical Associatication (AMA) defined learning environment as ‘a social system that includes the learner (including the external relationships and other factors affecting the learner), the individuals with whom the learner interacts, the setting(s) and purpose(s) of the interaction, and the formal and informal rules/policies/norms governing the interaction.’ \r\nComponent:\r\nAMA goes on to describe it as comprising three broad components in any institution or setting: institutional culture, curriculum (both formal and informal) and good educational climate\r\nInstitutional culture: Individual faculty and in