INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (116, 86, 'Title: Online environment is merely an extension of face-to-face learning environment - why? Describe the process of e-learning and its role in continuing professional development', 'Introduction:\r\n In just few years, electronic (e) learning has become part of the mainstream in medical education. While e-learning means many things to many people, at its heart it is about the educational uses of technology. Educational technologies can be used in support of virtually any aspect of medical education. E- Learning, e- teaching and e- assessment are related but distinct areas of activity. Integrated e- learning systems in the form of virtual learning environment (VLE) or learning management systems are now the norm.\r\nE-learning: In its broadest sense, e-learning is the use of internet for education. e-learning, often referred as online learning, is not simply a broadcast of documents in electronic format to students via internet rather e-learning encompasses a pedagogical approach that typically aspires to be flexible, engaging and learner-centered, one that encourages interaction (staff-staff, staff-student and student-student) and collaboration and communication, often asynchronously (though not exclusively so). \r\ne-learning: content and process\r\nThe ‘process vs. content’ assumes a particular meaning and significance in e-learning, whether the predominant focus should be on digital content or on the digitally mediated process. If an online course or programme is primarily about participating in activity, then the focus is more likely to be on scheduling, discussion and tracking activity, with content management being a relatively small part of system. Virtual learning environment (VLE) can be used for the purpose.\r\nThe content of online learning is not exhaustive. Course materials are perhaps the most common content considered in e-learning. Also included contents are e-library, commercial e-learning contents and uncountable online websites. \r\nSystems: LMS, VLE and MLE\r\nThe most common approach in e-learning or online learning is to use an integrated suite of tools and services typically called learning management system &#40;LMS&#41;, course management system &#40;CMS&#41; or VLE\r\nVLE functions and services\r\nThe common functions, tools and services of VLE are as follows, but all of them may not be suitable for a single course-\r\n Supporting resources such as syllabus or course outline\r\n Links to additional learning contents\r\n Key words for guiding e-learners to search online learning materials\r\n Discussion boards (forums)\r\n Chat rooms for synchronous communication\r\n Blogs\r\n Online examinations and tests (quiz)\r\n Portfolio tools\r\n Other online tools/resources\r\n Scheduling (calendaring/timetabling) etc.\r\n \r\nFacilitating online learning\r\nSynchronous and asynchronous text interaction\r\nOnline facilitation typically uses bulletin boards or chat rooms as the point of contact between students and facilitators. Many of the principles of face-to-face teaching and learning also apply here. In synchronous formal question and answer session, students and staff on line are actually in a scenario of lecture theatre. All participate in common issue, usually first raised by the facilitator. Informal asynchronous activities like queries around specific course content are also important component.\r\nAudio conferencing, video conferencing and web conferencing\r\nMultimedia alternatives are growing rapidly and increasingly being used in on line learning as important and growing educational media examples are video conferencing, web conferencing and audio conferencing.\r\nFace-to-face learning vs. online learning\r\nFace-to-face learning is the oldest, most conventional and traditional method used for teaching learning activity. It allows learners to interact with lecturer and peers, exchange views and ideas. It requires commonness in time, place and interest (as applicable) of the course, learners, facilitators and supporting staff, requires administrative and logistic supports, human and monitory resources. Barrier of traditional methods include family commitment, inability to get locum coverage, distance to travel, cost of attending courses and increased workload. On the other hand, on line environment, if up to the mark, can provide almost all components of face-to-face learning. It saves time. Video and web conferencing are almost face-to-face interaction among learners and teachers and are able to remove limitations of other on line techniques. Important is that, the learners and teachers are to have some computer literacy, have to have own computer, on line access, administrators are to provide and update information etc. The security of the whole matter is also important.\r\n\r\nConclusion\r\nEvery method in teaching learning activity has its inherent merits and demerits. One is not better than other in all perspectives; rather one should be complimentary to the other. So, on line teaching environment should be regarded as extension of face-to-face learning environment.\r\ne-learning and its role in continuing professional development\r\nDefinition of continuing professional development\r\nContinuing professional development (CPD) is the systematic maintenance, improvement and broadening of knowledge and the development of personal qualities necessary for the education of professionals throughout the working life. CPD is a broader concept including essential reference to the personal and social aspects of medical practice needed for high quality professional performance in modern health care delivery system.\r\nImportance of CPD\r\nCPD in medical education is simply required for good medical practice. CPD is important for its relevance in professional success, because-\r\n It helps in improving competence (skills and knowledge)\r\n To maintain up to date standard \r\n Maintain quality of care\r\n\r\nMethods for CPD\r\n Formal: conference, workshop, lectures, etc.\r\n Informal: short-term placements, etc.\r\n\r\nFollowing types of learning are now recognized as part of CPD\r\n Distance and open learning\r\n Computer based learning\r\n Computer assisted learning\r\n Problem oriented learning including self-management learning\r\n Structured learning including articles\r\n Writing technical reports\r\n Part time teaching\r\n Membership of relevant professional committee\r\n Skill development\r\n Short-term placements\r\n\r\ne-learning and CPD\r\nIt is obvious that for maintaining the standards of medical care, physicians are to be up to date in knowledge and skills. Aside from the formal CPD, practitioners are to be familiar with the current development in global scenario. Without using e-learning it is impossible to remain up to date. So, like formal CPD, on line or use of e-learning in CPD is important.\r\nConclusion\r\nCPD is an indispensible part of a professional and e-learning is probably the most important learning method in CPD.\r\n', '2018-02-09 02:07:56', 'upload/attachment/2d2c0a0ab1a83ad7a38c0b3b41ea14c6.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
