INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (118, 60, 'Plan to Improve Educational Environment and Staff Development Program in Our Department', 'I. Introduction:\r\nEducational environment or climate is a key aspect of the curriculum. It is less tangible than the content studied, teaching methods used or the examinations. It is nonetheless of equal importance. To achieve the aim of the curriculum students’ perception about educational environment is very important. Educational environment is also invaluable to develop in students a spirit of team work and collaboration. Our institute and medical college have many of the facilities, still there are lacking and scope of improvement. \r\nII. Scope of Improvement and Suggestions:\r\ni. Course/curriculum- the new curriculum 2012 that is effective now is theoretically excellent, according to the objectives and to equip students with knowledge, skill and attitude, professionalism and critical thinking, though there are problems with its implementation. \r\nii. Appropriate aims - aims are set, thought difficult to achieve with traditional institutional set-up. It will be wise to add guidelines, indicating facilities and changes needed for institution to achieve such aims. \r\niii. Organized- as traditional curriculum with basic sciences first and applied science with clinical medicine next. It will be better to start integrated teaching from the very beginning of the M.B.B.S. course.\r\niv. Contents- within the curriculum is also appropriate, but overburdened with topics regarding theory. There are appropriate practical topics as well, again needs guideline and suggestion for changes in the institutions to achieve and implement such contents (discussed below).\r\nv. Assessment system- are also very modern, but lacks diversity in questioning and feedback system due to lack of faculty training. \r\n\r\nIII. Teaching Method: \r\nTeaching methods suggested in the curriculum are very good. To practice these methods appropriately faculty training and continuing professional development are necessary.  \r\nIV. Teachers:\r\nMost of our teachers are enthusiastic and interested in quality teaching. Many of them have short, comprehensive (3days) training on medical education either in government institute or in Ibrahim Medical College (on self-payment), but none has precise training. All teachers in the department must be trained at a wider extent with medical education, contents of the curriculum and technics for their implementation and practice. A training can be started with senior teachers followed by juniors. There should have orientation program for new faculties. \r\nTeachers need to sit with students at the beginning of each compartment of clinical placement to orient them about the contents to be completed during that period what is expected of them at the end, and assessment method. \r\nV. Physical Environment:\r\ni. Library- \r\n• Our library needs expansion and modification in sitting arrangement with scope for individuals as well as group discussions.\r\n• Number of books need to be increased consisting of basic to advanced so that those who wish to build up career in surgery can be benefited since student-hood. \r\n• Electronic library- we need an electronic library with internet and its attendant resource facilities. CD and DVD on clinical examination, skill practice and different surgical procedures (basic to advanced) should be available. High quality images and sound clips are also important.\r\n• Copies of curriculum, academic calendar, time-table, study guide must be available in the library. \r\nii. Study guides- need to be made available for students mentioning objectives, contents and organization, teaching method, resources available, revision, glossary, illustrations and assessment method. \r\niii. Lectures- present practice is traditional and one-way (didactic method). We need to change/shift to interactive lecture. Students should be informed of the topic, aims and objectives, time allowed for self-study, interactive class, feedback (student to teacher, teacher to student)\r\niv. Tutorials- number of rooms need to increased and made free of distractions:\r\n• Small group- to ensure student participation and interaction, group work and reflection.\r\n• Need to be equipped with computers and audio-visual aids to facilitate teaching-learning and instant inter-active feedback.\r\nv. Clinical skill center- need to be established to avoid exclusive dependence on adhoc experience and hospital patients, equipped with models and manikins, simulated clinical environment, simulated and standardized patients (due to paucity of patients), necessary instruments. It will ensure one on one revision session and remedial training of students. \r\nvi. Procedure room- with facility of patients’ comfort and logistics, space and observation system for each student. \r\nvii. Operation theatre- traditional system of theatre placement of students has many limitations (contamination of OT environment, distractions during surgery, poor observation facilities for students). Modern facilities and space should be made available so that each student can equally observe the procedure and interact with the faculty. \r\nviii. Bedside teaching- To ensure distraction-free environment exclusive side rooms for pre/post round discussions as attendant control is almost impossible in our set-up. Presence of a nurse/student nurse during teaching to add multi-professional inputs.\r\nix. Patients- need to be briefed earlier so that they know what will be expected to them, feel a part of discussion and give feedback to students.\r\nx. Grand rounds, teaching ward round- to be started. \r\nxi. Ambulatory care teaching-need to be made more effective, extended to beyond need of examinations. \r\nxii. Log books- need to be made more effective through daily fill-up and signed by tutor. \r\nxiii. Community orientation- need to be incorporated in a short, discrete block of time through the mentorship of primary care doctors so that student can find relevance of what they been taught to be practice in real situation. \r\nxiv. Peer-assisted learning- may be started during block posting so that weaker students can feel free to learn from their friends. \r\nxv. Evidence-based medicine- at least one day in a month is devoted during clinical years of study. \r\n\r\nVI. Incorporation of DREEM- to evaluate educational environment\r\n\r\nVII. Staff development program: \r\nOur surgery department is part of two separate independent institutions (BIRDEM and IMC) with separate goals and interests of their own apart from individual faculty. BIRDEM is intended to have clinical services, IMC expects experts teaching skills, whereas, individual faculty expects successful career plan. To fulfill such outcomes many programs are run routinely and in adhoc basis in both institutes and in the department, but none have any structured program of staff development. So, we need to prepare a staff development program with goals and priorities set to balance individual and organization’s need and faculty motivation. \r\ni. Teaching skill – we need to train our teachers with comprehensive course of medical education. \r\n• Short course- available in government institute and IMC continued to be availed. Continuing medical education, one session in each month in BIRDEM need to be continued. \r\n• Peer coaching- faculties need initiatives not to soldiering on alone when other more experienced colleagues are around and are willing to assist. \r\n• Mentoring\r\n• orientation for new faculties\r\n• Scientific ethics and good practice\r\nAbove three facilities need to be newly started.\r\nii. Administrative skill- need to be started at a standard of foundation training for government officials.\r\niii. Research skill- three day short-course is available now in BIRDEM. It may be extended to a broad base so that faculties feel comfort in clinical research and scientific write-up. \r\niv. Clinical work- we have organizational (BIRDEM), departmental, unit-based practice of case presentation, mortality-morbidity meeting, and journal club run in regular basis. Our organization allows faculty members to participate in CME, workshops, seminars, and conferences at home and abroad, provide all possible support to arrange CME, workshops and seminars. These should be continued.\r\nWe need collaboration with other institutes at home and abroad with specific skill development facility so that faculties may get advanced training in respective field of clinical practice. \r\nFaculties need to have incentive in the form of credit for promotion who participates and take leadership in above programs.  \r\nv. Career planning- for junior faculties \r\nvi. Network building – our faculties are members of society and forum of their respective discipline (national and international). This need to be continued and encouraged for further extension so that they can remain updated and get ready for future advancement through active participation. \r\n\r\nVIII. Conclusion:\r\n“A medical schools most important asset is its faculty”. Academic vitality and advance clinical practice is dependent upon faculty member’s interest and expertise. We should remain innovative and flexible to accommodate the ever-changing needs of our teachers. Our institutions and the health care system in which we work. \r\n', '2018-02-10 00:37:58', 'upload/attachment/044527ed77214375a9de133edd4d5a04.docx', '<p>Dear fellow, It is well written indeed. The basic points would have been better if given in points</p><p>e.g. i) to set objectives of the department</p><p>ii) and how to reach those objectives</p><p>iii) How should be the teaching -learning environment, student-teacher ratio, class rooom facilities</p><p> iv) Assessment and feedback <br></p>', NULL, '2018-02-10 12:37:58', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (119, 89, 'Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment, discuss why? Describe the process of e-learning & its role in CPD.', '\r\n\r\nDr. Md. Towhidur Rahman                              I/D – GD2GOB\r\nName of the assignment – Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment, discuss why? Describe the process of e-learning & its role in CPD.\r\n\r\nOnline environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment –\r\nDefinition of online environment – It is an educational approach, culture context & physical setting where teaching & learning occur by using ICT (Information & communication technologies).\r\nPrinciples of e-learning – E-learning (often referred to as online learning) is not simply a broadcast of documents in electronic format to students via the internet, it encompasses a pedagogical approach that typically aspires to be flexible, engaging & learner-centered; one that encourages interaction (staff-staff, staff-student, student-student) and collaboration & communication, often asynchronously (through not exclusively so). Any course that employs e-learning might be run exclusively online or might be a mixture of online & face to face activities (Blended learning).\r\nReasons of online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment –\r\n1. The facilitator in e-learning may take the role being guide the student to work themselves through issues instead of supplying information only may take the role of the traditional facilitator.\r\n2. E-learning is now widely used in various forms of case based or problem based learning (PBL). \r\nPBL may be e-PBL or face to face e-PBL. e-PBL can be similar to standard PBL; the case is created & then distributed through e-mail or by posting into the VLE or in a system specifically designed for ePBL. Students interact with each other via chat rooms, bulletin boards, email or white boards. Face to face e-PBL is an extension of face to face learning environment.\r\n3. In blended e-learning a mixture of online & face to face activities used for learning is an extension of face to face learning.\r\n\r\n\r\n4.  Audio & video – A good way for novice e-teachers to begin using audio & video is to create sound or video files that can be placed on a website or VLE for download by students. Audio conferencing using VoIP (Voice over Internet Protocol) or tele conferencing by using skype, video conferencing & web conferencing as live lecture are extension of face to face learning environment.\r\n5. Syndicating content & casting – Audio & video files (often referred to as vodcasting) are streamed directly into the student’s device, using a format known as Really Simple Syndication (RSS) is an extension of face to face learning environment.\r\n6. Chat rooms are used for synchronous communication when students are dispersed but wish to attend a discussion simultaneously. Synchronous question & answer in a chat room where student & faculty meet online  as in lecture theatre as an extension of face to face learning environment.\r\n7. Discussion boards in e-learning (also known as bulletin boards or forums) are a means for participants to communicate asynchronously. This means that someone posts a message & others read & post replies at some later date or time; threads of discussion thereby build up over time as an extension of face to face learning environment.\r\n8. Blogs ( a shortened form of weblogs) in e-learning typically take the form of a personal online journal , usually written by one individual, but open to be read by all . Each new post is added on top of previous post is as an extension of face to face learning environment.\r\nDescribe the process of e-learning :\r\nAny learning experience supported by ICT often referring to as online learning. The term e-learning describes the use of the new electronic technologies including the internet to facilitate learning. It includes-\r\n• The online delivery of course content\r\n• Discussion forums\r\n• Online tutoring or mentoring\r\n• Bulletin boards\r\n• Synchronous communication & instant chat\r\n• Online assessment\r\n• Offline resources such as CDs & DVDs.\r\n        \r\n\r\n\r\n      Processes of e-learning includes –\r\n1. Schedules (Study guides)\r\n2. Rules\r\n3. Protocols\r\n4. Online discussion\r\n5. Chat\r\n6. Conferencing (Teleconferencing, skype, web conferencing, audio & video conferencing)\r\n7. By accessing specific e-learning content.\r\n8. By taking tests & assessments (Formative & summative e-assessment)\r\n9. Working through short exercise to stimulate thinking.\r\n10. Completing web forms such as those used in e-Portfolios or course evaluation.\r\n11. Communicating by email or online searching.\r\n\r\nRole of e-learning in CPD (Continuing Professional Development)\r\nCPD is a combination of approaches, techniques & ideas that will help professionals to maintain, manage continuous improvement & enhance own learning. The benefit of CPD is keeping a professional up to date with current knowledge & competence.\r\n1. E-learning is offering the ease of access, so crucial to learners.\r\n2. Online CPD (CME) is ideally suited to meet the CRISIS criteria of Convenience, Relevance, Individualization, Self assessment, Independent learning & systematic approach to learning.\r\n3. E-learning reduce the impact of the traditional CME barriers such as – family commitments, distance travel, costs of attending courses, increased workload, lack of time etc.\r\n', '2018-02-13 18:37:14', 'upload/attachment/a8f157e95561411f6271533c269469a0.docx', '<p>congratulation. your assignment is accepted. </p>', NULL, '2018-02-14 06:37:14', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (120, 85, 'e-Learning and CPD', '', '2018-02-09 05:21:25', 'upload/attachment/e78410e1f57b7301e5c62f50558b5e8e.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (121, 88, 'Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment’, Discuss why? Describe the process of e-learning and its role in CPD', 'Assignment No: 4\r\nModule: 1 Contemporary issues in medical education\r\nUnit: CI4 “Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment’, Discuss why? Describe the process of e-learning and its role in CPD”\r\nFellow ID: 181020\r\nThe world of education has been varied by the fast and rapid revolution in computer and the Internet technologies. The arrival of World Wide Web (WWW) has increased the demand for distance education and concepts like online learning or e- learning has emerged, as a result. \r\nIn the online learning environment, teaching and learning take place through the use of computers, internet and computer mediated digital systems. It is also called the e-learning environment \r\ne-learning might be exclusively online or might be a mixture of online and face to face activities, called blended learning .\r\n\r\nOnline environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment because-\r\n• In face to face learning, there is facilitator.  Online environments also allow students to take turns as a moderator or facilitator and learn much more from the process. Online facilitation uses bulletin boards or chat rooms as the point of contact between students and facilitators.\r\n• All forms of group work requires participation. In face to face learning, this participation occurs physically in classroom, campus and in online environment they collaborate with others by reading, responding and posting messages via e-mail, chat room, and/or whiteboard\r\n• In online learning learners get to know about the course content and exam schedules by reading course module notes, e-mail messages and postings to discussion area.\r\n• In a classroom setting, the instructor may often pose a question. In many cases, the question leads to a serious discussion and debate with other students. This also occurs in the online classroom through the use of discussion topics in the discussion area by audio, video and web conferencing by the use of skype, MSN . \r\n• In online learning, e-assessment is taken by the use of ICT for authoring, delivering, marking, providing feedback and analyzing of both formative and summative student assessment.\r\n• In a classroom setting, classmates typically meet before or after class for a cup of coffee and a bit of socializing. This can still occur in the online environment using e-mail, the discussion area or chat rooms. Everyone likes know a bit about the people they are studying with.\r\n• There are also e-Logistics and e- administration which support the administration and logistics of learning environment\r\nMany of the principles of face to face teaching and learning also apply to online learning environment. Many technological tools and different social media devices  minimize the distance between students and to make online classes as interesting as face-to-face ones.\r\nAs seen, e-learning can be as great as the face-to face learning environment. These facts show that students will be more benefited from online classes if the course is a blend of online and face- to face learning, then one can easily emphasise that “Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment”.\r\nProcess of e-learning:\r\nThe process of e-learning begins with a comprehensive analysis of learners, learning content, and context and ends with performing a quality check. The e-learning process includes several stages: analysis, planning, design, development, delivery, and evaluation.\r\n\r\n\r\ne-learning process can be divided into two major phases:\r\n1) Content preparation\r\n2) Content implementation \r\nContent preparation\r\nContent preparation phase consists of activities including analysis, planning, design, development and evaluation.\r\nIn analysis stage learning goals and objectives are established and learner’s knowledge and skills are identified. It is a broad process.\r\nOn the basis of analysis stage, a comprehensive e- learning plan can be developed and it serves as road map.\r\nThe design of e- learning follows a logical and orderly method of organizing course contents with learning objectives, relevant learning strategies, assessment instruments, exercise and delivery media.\r\nContent implementation \r\nDuring the implementation phase all e-content is distributed to or is accessible by its stakeholder groups at anytime from anywhere in the world. In this phase, all e-learning content is uploaded to the server (usually all e-content is hosted on LMSs - Learning Management Systems or LCMSs). \r\nAll supplemental course materials (e.g., CD, DVD, audio and video cassette, book, course pack, etc.) are also delivered to its stakeholder groups. Before offering an e-learning course to its target population, an institution should have an efficient administrative system to register students, experienced technical support system to maintain and update e-learning content. \r\nInstitution should have a procedure for training instructors and facilitators on course curriculum, learning outcomes, method of delivery, and testing procedures. Similar procedures should be in place for technical and other support staff and students.\r\nInstitution must employ a system of updating and monitoring of all e-learning materials on a regular basis. During this stage it is critical that all internal and external links and resources are active, and all security measures are in place.\r\nRole of e-learning in CPD-\r\nContinuing professional development (CPD) involves not only educational activities to enhance medical competence in medical knowledge and skills, but also in management, team building, professionalism, interpersonal communication, technology, teaching, and accountability.\r\nIt is an ongoing process and continues throughout a professional’s career. \r\nThe traditional method of CPD are face -to- face courses, seminars or it may be informal, such as reading of journals and texts, which are not always possible. Traditional CPD include family commitments, lack of time, distances to travel and increased work load. e-learning can play very important role to overcome these barriers. \r\n e-learning-\r\n• Provides online courses on CPD\r\n• Makes the course convenient \r\n• Makes the course schedule and environment flexible \r\n• Makes the course relevant\r\n• Provides individual, independent learning approach\r\n• Provides systematic learning approach\r\n• Provides opportunity of self assessment and feedback\r\n• Save time for other professional and personal activities\r\n• Maintains privacy and confidentiality of the learner\r\nTraditional method along with e-learning can make the CPD successful. Every doctor has a personal responsibility to participate in continuing professional development. Institutions should accept responsibility for both CME and CPD of doctors, establish effective CPD schemes and strategies to meet the needs of doctors, the populations they serve, and the organizations where they work.                                                   \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-02-13 22:07:24', 'upload/attachment/1f60cb9553be2b571a0e4357fe2414c9.doc', '<p>Dear fellow</p><p>Your assignment accepted. But the assaignment not indicating your clear concept.</p><p>Any Learning by using ICT is e-learning. It may be exclusively by online or blended.</p><p>The learner get the opportunity to interact directly with the teacher/instructor in face to face learning environment.</p><p>In blended learning, formal question-answer session in chat room, bulletin board, teleconferencing,audio conferencing,video conferencing are the learning environment, where the learner get the opportunity to directly interact with the teacher/ instructor. All are merely extension of face to face learning environment.</p><p>CPD is continuous improvement & self-development to be up-to-date professional.</p><p>Lot of  barrier either be personal or institutional or time limitation or resource in traditional way of CPD may overcome in e-learning.</p><p> Prof Md Shah Alam.</p>', NULL, '2018-02-14 10:07:24', 'F');
