INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (135, 93, 'Differentiate teaching from instruction using suitable examples. Prepare an instructional text for your students following the rules of instructional design theory (your own discipline). ', 'Differentiate teaching from instruction using suitable examples. Prepare an instructional text for your students following the rules of instructional design theory (your own discipline). \r\n', '2018-02-20 12:31:48', 'upload/attachment/6e995c8236d2d24bb9945e19b3305e4d.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (136, 106, 'Title: Differentiating teaching from instruction using suitable examples. Prepare an instructional text for your students of your own discipline following the rules of instructional design theory', 'Introduction\r\nInstruction is a human activity and its purpose is to help people learn. Instruction is a set of events which affect learner in such a way that learning is ultimately facilitated like enzyme acts as biocatalyst. The conception of teaching is not about transmitting information or imparting knowledge but about facilitating student learning. Instruction may be a printed page, picture, television program or combination of any physical objects. Teaching although consider as one form of instruction but it is the single most important one among all other instructions. A handout on contents in topic “UTI” may be supplied to students containing reading lists including definition, aetiology, clinical features, investigations and treatment, which is an instruction and a later taken lecture class (teaching learning session) on UTI may be an example of teaching.\r\nSo, Instruction is a broad heading under which teaching is a form of instruction which facilitates learning.\r\n                                                                     My instructional text on UTI \r\nInstructional design theories concerned with arranging external events that support internal process of the learner to achieve learning outcome .Every teacher should have specific and detailed knowledge of the intent and purpose of each of the instructional events. There are several instructional design theories of these; Robert Gagne proposed a series of events which follow a systematic instructional design process that share the behaviorist approach to learning with a focus on the outcome of instruction or training\r\nThe following nine steps have been adapted from Gagne, Briggs, and Wager (1992)\r\n1. Gaining attention: The purpose of this event is to focus learners on the tasks to be learned by presenting an interesting event, telling a relevant story or showing a picture. It is important to remember that attention must be maintained throughout the session for effective learning\r\n2. Inform the learning objective- it is important because the learners need to know what they are to learn and to achieve\r\nObjective-\r\na. Definition of UTI\r\nb.  common organisms causing UTI\r\nc. Pathophysiology\r\nd. Diagnosis\r\ne. Management and\r\nf. Follow up\r\n3. Stimulate recall of prior learning- help students make sense of new information by relating it to something they already know or something they have already experienced.\r\nMethods for stimulating recall include:\r\n Have you seen the patient of UTI?\r\n Ask few common questions like why female are more prone to UTI? \r\n What is the most common organism?\r\n4. Present the content- it is considered as the core of teaching. In this event, the fact, the concept and principles of learning to be focused in a structured way so, that learner can understand. Same content of instruction of multiple version provide added facilitation e.g. video, demonstration. In sometime use a variety of media to address different learning preferences.\r\n5. Provide learning guidance- advice students of strategies to aid them in learning content and of                        resources available.\r\n Methods to provide learning guidance include: \r\n-Provide instructional support as needed-as scaffold (cues, hints, prompt) which can be    removed after they learn the task or content.\r\n-Model varied learning strategies-mnemonics, concept mapping, role playing\r\n-Use examples and non-examples\r\n6. Elicit performance (practice) – this event provides the occasion for learners to practice or checks that the students have learned\r\n Ways to activate learner processing include: \r\n-Elicit student activities - palpate the lower abdomen, elicit renal angle whether tender or not \r\n-Elicit recall strategies-ask them to recite, revisit or reiterate information they have learned\r\n- Help them integrate new knowledge\r\n7. Providing feedback on performance-feedback for student very much essential for learning. It help student for assessing performance as well as facilitate learning. There are different type of feedback\r\n-Confirmatory feedback-Inform the student they did what he/she were suppose to do.\r\n-Corrective and remedial feedback- Inform the student the accuracy of their performance     or response\r\n-Remedial feedback-Directs students in the right direction to find the correct answer but does not provide the correct answer\r\n-Informative feedback-Provides information (New, different, addition or suggestions) for listening as well as sharing between them\r\n-Analytical feedback- provide the student with suggestions, recommendations and information for them to correct their performance\r\n8. Assessing the performance-is concerned with complete demonstration of learning outcomes at the end of instruction. It conform that the learning has taken place. For expected complete learning we must test to see improvement  \r\nMethods for testing learning include:  \r\n -Conduct a post test to check for mastery of content or skills\r\n-Include objective or criterion-referenced performances which measure how well a student has    learned a topic\r\n-Identify a normative-referenced performance which compares one student to another student\r\n9. Enhance retention and transfer to job- to help learners develop expertise, they must internalize new knowledge  \r\nConclusion: Ganges nine event of instruction can help build the framework with which to prepare and deliver instructional content. Ideally we should prepare course goals and learning objectives before implementing the nine events. The nine events of instruction can then be modified to fit both the content to be presented and student’s level of knowledge.\r\n\r\n                    \r\n', '2018-02-22 01:31:59', 'upload/attachment/435f3f4ad91496e96ae0a6d500ee9ce6.docx', '<p>Your overall writing is very good but if you write instructional text for your student, following the style I have attached here would be even better. Question should be given on the left hand side of the text , need to put some picture as well with some references.</p>', 'upload/attachment/3aeb3c1754633ac0d7379231c25b5603.docx', '2018-02-23 11:13:30', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (137, 96, 'Instructional text for the topic\" Bipolar Mood Disorder\" following the rules of Gagne\'s Nine Events of Instruction', 'Emphasis in medical education should be firmly on how students can apply their knowledge in solving problems that is on what they can do rather than what they know so the thrust of teaching is to be on facilitating learning rather than on covering the subject. But, as Light & Cox (2001) point out, teachers have a responsibility which takes them beyond facilitating the “construction” of knowledge to assisting and supporting the student to develop as persons. In achieving this, the process of instructional design is significant. \r\nTeaching almost always implies having a teacher. Instruction can come from a piece of paper or a book. Teaching is more complex in nature. When we talk about teaching, we are dealing with different techniques, strategies, and approaches that will facilitate learning. Teachers have to come up with varied instructional materials and must use the right strategies in teaching their lessons. \r\nTeaching is also a never ending process. By the time individuals start going to school to the time they graduate and start working, they\'re involved in the teaching-learning process. They don\'t only learn from teachers but also from those around them. \r\nThis makes teaching both formal and informal. It is formal when it occurs inside the classroom or informal when you learn things outside the portals of the school. For instance, we learn to read and write in school with the help of your teachers. On the other hand, our parents teach us informally about living life and correct values. \r\nWhen we talk about instruction, it\'s not as complex as teaching. Instruction is simply giving direction. We instruct someone on what to do and how to do it. For instance, in school we\'re given instructions by our teachers on how to answer a test or how to perform an experiment. After which, we\'re simply left to do our work on our own. \r\nInstruction makes learners dependent on the teacher. We\'re told what to do and oftentimes, there are steps we need to follow. Instructions must be understood and followed strictly in order to accomplish a particular task. Once we fail to do so, we won\'t be able to finish the task correctly. \r\nTeaching and instruction go together especially in education. Both are needed in helping people learn and develop as individuals.\r\nInstructional text for students (Bipolar mood disorder)\r\n1. Gaining attention of the student\r\nShow a video of a manic patient\r\nPresenting some alarming facts, like\r\n    Mortality is about twice in bipolar patients\r\n    Rates of suicide 15 times higher in bipolar even higher in depression\r\n2. Informing students about the objectives/ learning outcomes-\r\n   The video shows that the patient is difficult to handle by the attendant and the facts shows that there is risk if untreated, so \r\n            I)We have to learn- (Cognitive domain)\r\nDefinition\r\nEpidemiology\r\nEtiology\r\nClinical features\r\nDifferential diagnosis\r\nManagement\r\nPrognosis of Bipolar mood disorder\r\nii) We have to acquire the skill of interviewing and managing the patient practically (Psychomotor domain)\r\niii) We have to realize the problems of the attendants and showing empathy to them and give some advices needed accordingly (Affective domain)\r\n\r\n3. Stimulating recall of prior learning-\r\n     Asking about previous concept of - mood, depression, hallucination, delusions, mood stabilizer and other psychotropic drugs, mental state examination etc.\r\n4. Presenting the content-\r\n    Organize and chunk content in a meaningful way. Provide explanations after demonstration. Give examples. Asking questions and giving clues to answer.\r\n5. Providing learning guidance-\r\n     Group work/ Psychodrama/Role play (Mental state examination of a Manic patient) & Case studies to discuss contents.\r\n6. Eliciting performance-\r\n      To elicit recall, asking students to recite/revisit information after Role play\r\n7. Providing feedback\r\n            Inform the students about accuracy of their performance of interviewing a patient of Bipolar mood disorder in role play and provide the student with suggestions, recommendations, and information for them to correct their performance \r\n8. Assess performance\r\n      By embedding questions throughout instruction through oral questioning and or quizzes\r\n9. Enhance retention and transfer to the job-\r\n       Summarize the topic and provide additional resources to help student internalize new knowledge.\r\n\r\nWe must have appropriate media as tool and alternate arrangement in case of emergency if it does not support the class. There should be a non-threatening environment in the class. Teachers must include new attempts to keep the lesion interesting for the students, and change the lesion plan accordingly in every lecture.\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n\r\n1. https://uk.answers.yahoo.com/question/index?qid=20121005042739AAR94Cp\r\n2. ABC of Learning and Teaching in Medicine\r\n3. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n4. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education; 2013. First edition.\r\n', '2018-02-22 10:06:49', 'upload/attachment/87ff0f1b3825799550b3c32d1fd0ea26.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (138, 99, 'Differentiate teaching from instruction using suitable examples. Prepare an instructional text for your students following the rules of instructional design theory (in your discipline).', '\r\nDr. Md. Towhidur Rahman\r\nName of assignment – Differentiate teaching from instruction using suitable examples. Prepare an instructional text for your students following the rules of instructional design theory (in your discipline).\r\n\r\n                                     Difference between Instruction & Teaching\r\nInstruction Teaching\r\nPlanned activities that facilitates learning eg- text, video, demonstration, lecture, group work, printed page, picture etc. Interaction between teacher & student under teacher’s responsibility to achieve learning objective.\r\nWorks for skill development. Works for overall development.\r\nArouse only thinking & aims for producing carbon copy. Arouse critical thinking & aims for producing new products.\r\nTeacher may not be present during an instruction e.g. Study guide, instructional text. Teacher must present during a teaching session.\r\nAll instruction are not teaching. All teaching are an instruction.\r\nBoth instructors & learners are important. Teachers play crucial role.\r\nInstruction is primarily one directional from an instructor to student. Teaching is bidirectional (From teacher’s perspective it is teaching, from student’s perspective it is learning).\r\nExamples –\r\nDesign lessons based on students learning objectives, Using appropriate media, Asses students by using formative assessment, Manage classroom to create a safe & supportive environment. Examples-\r\nHelping students to understand content, Creating curriculum, Collaborating students to create guide, Starting class with a story, Using on demand arrange summative assessment, Feedback. \r\n\r\n\r\nInstructional text for the students in the department of Radiology & Imaging-\r\nText- To improve the ability of the students for Ultrasound (USG) guided pleural fluid aspiration in department of Radiology & Imaging.\r\nDefinition of instructional design- It may be defined as knowledge & skill to develop an effective instructional strategies that meet the needs of the learner to achieve desired goal / learning objective.\r\nThe following instructional texts may be adapted to improve the ability of the students for USG guided pleural fluid aspiration in department of Radiology & Imaging-\r\n\r\n1. Gain attention of the students-\r\nStimulate students with surprise by presenting a new method of Intervention Radiology of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration both for diagnostic & therapeutic purpose.\r\n2. Inform students of the objectives-\r\nTo describe the procedure of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration in sitting position of the patient.\r\n3. Stimulate recall of prior learning-\r\n• By asking questions to students about previous experience of Ultrasound & USG appearance of pleural effusion.\r\n• Pre tests may be taken about USG, pleural effusion, previous concepts about USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n4. Present the content-\r\n• To provide more effective, efficient instruction about USG guided pleural fluid aspiration and explanations are given after demonstration.\r\n• Present vocabulary.\r\n• Provides examples about the technique of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• Present multiple versions of the content e.g. video, demonstration, lecture, group work.\r\n5. Providing learning guidance-\r\n• Aid the students in learning content & resources available, ie visit website (www.med. USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.ca.com) or reading book (Interventional USG of chest. Joltmollah, 2007)\r\n• Provide case studies, visual image, video associated with USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• Provide instructional support (cues, hints) for USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n6. Elicit performance (practice)-\r\n• Elicit student activities by asking deep learning questions about the procedure of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• Elicit student about recall strategies to revisit or reiterate information about USG guided pleural fluid aspiration they have learned.\r\n• Help students integrate new knowledge if failed to aspirate USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n7. Provide feedback-\r\n• Confirmatory feedback- By informing students about USG guided pleural fluid aspiration what he or she were supposed to do.\r\n• Corrective & remedial feedback- Informing the students about their accuracy of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• Informative feedback- provides new technique and suggestion about USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• Analytic feedback- providing students with suggestions, recommendations & information to correct their performance.\r\n\r\n8. Assess performance-\r\n• By conducting a post test to check for skills in USG guided pleural fluid aspiration.\r\n• By embed questions throughout instruction by oral questioning &/or quizzes.\r\n\r\n9. Enhance retention & transfer to the job-\r\nBy providing additional resources & references of USG guided pleural fluid aspiration like books (Rumack USG manual book), students may internalize new knowledge.\r\n', '2018-02-23 08:24:41', 'upload/attachment/64fbc77df2114d1317b22b28a5ea7d95.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
