INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (147, 92, 'Assignment-1 Differentiate Teaching from Instruction Using Suitable Examples, Assignment-2 Prepare an Instructional Text for Your Students following the Rules of Instructional Design Theory', 'Assignment-1\r\nDifferentiate Teaching from Instruction Using Suitable Examples\r\n\r\n1. Introduction:\r\nLearning is facilitated by teaching. The teacher has to communicate with learners for effective teaching. Instruction acts as a means of communication among teacher and learners in a systematic way. \r\n\r\n2. Teaching:\r\nTeaching may be defined as an organized communication between the teachers and the students, concerned with providing students with opportunities to learn. It encompasses course design, course management and methods of teaching, provision of other learning opportunities, assessment and feedback of students. It is an intentional activity and interactive process among teacher, student and tasks. \r\nTeacher’s concept of teaching vary greatly, some are happy to ‘covering the subject’, others claim that they are ‘imparting information’ and still others are ‘imparting knowledge’. They emphasis on the content of the subject and their teaching of it. This type of teaching is ‘teachers-centered’ and content oriented. In this process, the student will get a sufficient grasp of the subject to be able to answer the questions raised in an examinations in the form of recall of factual information. Here learning is often thought as a single uniform process, there are little or no distinction made between “learning to load a rifle and learning to solve a complex mathematical problem”. \r\nThis trend is changing, now there are teachers who are facilitating student learning, adopt an approach to teaching that is “student-centered and learning oriented”. \r\n\r\n3. Instruction:\r\nFor effective teaching, the teacher has to communicate with the learners. Instructional materials act as means of communicating ideas from the teacher to the learners, thus help to achieve learning goals. Instructional design can be considered as a process through which teacher can identify the nature of the learning that is intended to take place, work out an approach to teaching that will facilitate the achievement of that learning and administer an appropriate assessment that will determine whether the intended learning has taken place. Instructions may be defined as “the set of plannred external events which influence the process of learning and thus promote learning” (Robert Gangne). In this process the student is encourage to adopt “deep approach” to learning and its expected to understand and apply the knowledge acquired. \r\nThe steps of the instruction include need assessment, objective, medium, implementation and evaluation. There is an interaction among the components of instruction- learner characteristics, objective, methods, and evaluation. Revision of evaluation guide to review or set new objectives and nature of instruction. There are various theories of instruction which are concerned with arranging external events that supports internal process of learning to achieve learning outcome on the basis of understanding of how students learn. These theories provide guidelines for organizing the activities teachers should do (external to mind) that influence on inside the learner’s mind (internal to mind), so that they can learn easily. Thus teaching-learning is made more structured and effective to achieve the learning objectives. \r\n\r\n4. Example\r\nA teacher prepare a power point presentation in his laptop on the topic ‘Acute Appendicitis’ including introduction, anatomy (with microscopy), acute appendicitis, etiology, pathology, clinical diagnosis (history, symptoms, clinical signs), differential diagnosis (according to age), investigation, treatment, appendisectomies and their consequences with management. He used multimedia to deliver the lecture in the class using that power point presentation, provided necessary explanation, showed relevant pictures and video clips, asked questions to assess students’ understanding and retention. \r\nAn instructor provided instructions on ‘Acute Appendicitis’. He gained attention of the students by saying the story of Appendicitis of one of his friend when he was college student, then he informed the learning objectives of acute appendicitis, initiated discussions by asking questions to assess pre-requisite knowledge like ‘what are the different anatomical positions of the appendix’, then proceed to the topic ‘Appendicitis’, provided guidelines, allowed group discussions, showed diagnostic physical examinations and asked students to practice, provided feedback on examination and assessed their performances. Finally he summarized the whole topic and concluded with the advice to go through some books. \r\n\r\n5. Conclusion:\r\nThe purpose of teaching is to facilitate learning. The instructional design process is a valuable and comprehensive aid in this task since it involves the identification of nature of learning that is intended to take place. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAssignment-2\r\nPrepare an Instructional Text for Your Students following the Rules of Instructional Design Theory\r\n\r\nTitle:\r\nEliciting rebound tenderness in a patient with acute appendicitis.\r\n1. Gaining attention- by showing a video clip of examination of a patient with acute appendicitis\r\n2. Informing the learning objectives\r\nAt the end of the session, students will be able to:\r\n• Show the steps of eliciting rebound tenderness \r\n3. Stimulating pre-requisite knowledge\r\nInitiate discussion by asking questions about anatomy of the appendix, acute appendicitis, etiology, pathology, clinical diagnosis, special features according to the position of the appendix, age of the patient and pregnancy state, differential diagnosis etc. \r\n4. Presenting stimulus material\r\n• List the pre-requisites of physical examination\r\n Greeting\r\n Introduce yourself to the patient\r\n Seek permission for examination\r\n Arrange for privacy\r\n Arrange for good lighting\r\n Positioning of the patient (supine)\r\n Exposure of the part to be examined (mid-chest to mid-thigh)\r\n Warming your hands\r\n• Explain the steps of eliciting rebound tenderness \r\n Ask the patient to relax his abdomen by slow, deep breathing. \r\n Apply gentle but firm pressure over the Mc. Burney’s point with the flat of your right hand standing on the right side of the patient keeping eyes towards the face of the patient.  \r\n Suddenly release the pressure off and observe patient’s facial expression of sharp pain as the hand is removed. \r\n• Show the examination by yourself\r\n• Thanks the patient for cooperation \r\n5. Providing learning guidance\r\nGive a checklist to the patient which covers the above criteria. \r\n6. Eliciting the performance\r\nGive opportunity to the learners to practice \r\n7. Provide feedback on performance to confirm the accuracy of the performance and suggest how to improve\r\n8. Assessing the performance\r\n• Ask the students to demonstrate the rebound tenderness \r\n9. Enhancing retention and transfer\r\n• Summarize the session\r\n• Ask learners to practice on dummy patients\r\n• Ask to review the video clip \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-02-23 10:18:39', 'upload/attachment/097b6de75b8d0891c01a6dbaf43f66b0.docx', '<p>you have written very well but it could have been even better if you follow the template attached with your feedback</p>', 'upload/attachment/f1253d6465c3009ca9f327b2447b7416.docx', '2018-02-25 23:01:44', 'F');
