INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (179, 141, ' Skeletal Handout on \"Dealing with Challenging Patients\"', 'Dealing with Challenging Patients \r\n\r\nViolence against doctors is an increasing problem. \r\n \r\nThe most at risk are-\r\n Doctors working in emergency departments, \r\n General practitioners, \r\n Psychiatrists, and  \r\n Doctors in training.\r\n\r\nDoctors could be spat at, kicked, punched, bitten, or even stabbed by patients or their relatives/friends. One in three of the doctors physically assaulted is injured, 5% seriously.\r\nOver a 12 month period 63% of family physicians had some experience of violence, while 18% experienced some sort of abuse at least once a month. (In a city in UK, 1991)\r\nThere is no proper training of health care professionals on how to handle the challenging situation.\r\n Patients, and sometimes their attendants show challenging behavior that may take the form of:\r\n• Being demanding or controlling \r\n• Unwillingness to listen/uncooperative\r\n• Verbal abuse or threats\r\n• Physical violence against people or property.\r\n Most people who are violent have a mental disorder\r\n              True / False?\r\n              Why ?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhy do patients become ‘challenging’?\r\nUnwell or in pain\r\nDrink/substance misuse\r\nFear, anxiety or distress\r\nCommunication or language difficulties\r\nUnrealistic expectations \r\nPrevious poor experience\r\nFrustration & Guilt  \r\n   \r\nTo Identifying the problem, Questions are-\r\n Is it the patient?\r\n    Medical/ Psychiatric problem\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Is it lack of resources?\r\n     Long waiting times/lack of available appointments or beds/poor communication by staff\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Is it the doctor?\r\n      Competing pressures on the doctor (time, resources, personal) \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nManagement of Challenging patients\r\n If physical/medical cause suspected: \r\nSedative medication for proper examination, \r\nActive medical management & transfer \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n If psychiatric cause suspected: \r\nPharmacological management, \r\nCompulsory detention, review current management & transfer for proper care.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n If no physical or psychiatric cause suspected: Inform security or police to have person removed.\r\n When the person has offensive weapon/ a hostage situation/threatening suicide:  \r\nThis is a police matter & our responsibility does not extend to risking own or other people’s lives in trying to deal with the situation.\r\n\r\nBefore interviewing we always have to consider:  \r\n• Self-protection\r\n• Have proper interview setup including others in the vicinity.\r\n• Have others present during the assessment if needed.\r\n• Know as much as possible about the patients before meeting them.\r\n• Attend to developing an alliance with the patient.\r\n• Reassure, calm or assist the patient’s reality testing.\r\n• Offer medication to control aggressiveness.\r\n• Inform the patient that restraint or seclusion will be used if necessary.\r\n• Have teams ready to restrain the patient.\r\n• Leave physical restraint procedures to those who are trained.\r\n• Immediately plan a further approach.\r\n• Use of restraints-\r\n\r\n1. Preferably five or a minimum of four persons should be used to restrain the patient. \r\n2. Leather restrains are the safest and surest type of restraints.\r\n3. Explain to the patient why he or she is going into restraints. \r\n4. Patient should be restrained with legs spread eagled and one arm restrained to one side and the other arm restrained over patient’s head.\r\n \r\n\r\n5. The patient’s head is raised slightly to decrease the patient’s feelings of vulnerability & the possibility of aspiration.\r\n6. A staff member should always be visible and reassuring the patient who is being restrained.\r\n7. Restrains should be placed so that intravenous fluids can be given, if necessary. \r\n8. The restrains should be checked periodically for safety and comfort.\r\n9. After the patient is in restraints, the clinician begins treatment, using verbal intervention.\r\n10. 9. After the patient is under control, one   restraint at a time should be removed at 5-minute intervals until the patient has only two restraints on. Both of the remaining restraints should be removed at the same time.\r\n11. Always thoroughly document the reason for restraints, the course of treatment, and the patient’s response to treatment while in restraints.\r\nPharmacological approach to violent behavior-\r\nDos and Don’ts:\r\n Follow local protocols where available.\r\n Document all decisions and actions.\r\n Have a low threshold for obtaining senior advice.\r\n Always prescribe oral and I/M doses separately to avoid confusion.\r\n Do not mix medications in the same syringe.\r\n Do not use two different drugs of same class for rapid tranquillization.\r\n\r\nPotential risks of Pharmacological management-\r\n1. Over-sedation causing loss of consciousness and alertness.\r\n2. Cardiovascular or respiratory collapse.\r\n3. Interaction with prescribed or elicit medication.\r\n4. Damage to therapeutic relationship \r\n\r\nA guide to rapid tranquillization:\r\n First line –\r\n Non psychotic context – Oral Lorazepam (1–2mg)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\nPsychotic context -- Oral Lorazepam 1–2mg and oral anti-psychotic \r\n                                     (Haloperidol 10-20 mg, chlorpromazine 50 – 100 mg)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Second line- \r\n               (Oral medication failed or refused or not indicated)\r\n               \r\n                Non psychotic context- IM Lorazepam 1-2 mg\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n               Psychotic context- \r\n IM Lorazepam 1-2 mg plus IM Haloperidol 10–20 mg  or \r\n IM Olanzapine  or\r\n IM Chlorpromazine 25 – 100 mg  or\r\n IM Depot zuclopenthixol acetate 50 – 150 mg \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n Exceptional circumstances – Immediate tranquillization necessary –\r\n  IV Benzodiazepine (e.g. Diazepam 10 mg) \r\n  IV Haloperidol 2 – 10 mg\r\n\r\n\r\n Third line -\r\n  Other treatments (e.g. paraldehyde) or combinations of the above \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAfter care:\r\n Respiration, pulse, BP should be monitored within an hour of drug administration and regularly thereafter.\r\n Look for EPSs, particularly acute dystonia, possible NMS.\r\n Remember: Fatalities have occurred during emergency restraints. \r\nPredicting the human nature is not easy & predicting the nature of Bangladeshi people is even more difficult. And thus after taking all these steps, things still can go wrong and in that case we cannot but agree with, P Madhok who wrote-\r\n“There is something to be said for young doctors who should learn Martial arts. The world is increasingly progressing towards violence. So martial arts are worthwhile learning for self-defense. It will boost the doctor’s confidence even if not used.”\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nReferences & further reading-\r\n1. D’Urso P, Hobbs R: Aggression and the general practitioner.British Medical Journal 1989, 298:97-98.\r\n2. Goodman RA, Jenkins EL, Mercy JA: Workplace-related homicide among health care workers in the United States, 1980 through 1990. JAMA 1994, 272:1686-1688.\r\n3. Violence against Physicians Frederick et al. J GEN INTERN MED 1994;9: 503- 506.\r\n4. Derazon H, Nissimian S, Yosefy C, Peled R, Hay E: [Violence in the emergency department] [Hebrew]. Harefuah 1999, 137:95-101\r\n5. Violence Against Doctors P Madhok Bombay Hospital Journal, Vol. 51, No. 2, 2009\r\n6.  [Assault and kidnap of a specialist doctor]. The Daily Kaler Kantho 2010 May 10 [Bengali]\r\n7. Shorter Oxford Handbook of Psychiatry, 3rd Edition.\r\n\r\nDr. Nasim Jahan\r\nMBBS, FCGP, CCD, MCPS, FCPS                                                \r\nAssistant Professor,  Psychiatry\r\nBIRDEM General Hospital & IMC\r\n', '2018-03-08 06:52:11', 'upload/attachment/ebef92862e317c8cd31e3f212bb30d54.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
