INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (184, 136, 'Prepare one summarized or skeletal handouts of a lecture on any topic related to your subjects for the students', 'Introduction:\r\nHandouts comprise any form of written material or sample which is distributed to the participants of a course or group. The hand out is usually intended to reinforce or illustrate what has been presented by the tutor. It may also acts as a summary or contains a series of instructions for what the participants are expected to do next.\r\nA hand out is prepared by the teacher to and distributed to the student before, during and after giving lecture. Each hand out should have a clear purpose relating directly to the content of the material.\r\nSome tutor like to convert overhead transparencies or multimedia slides into handout. To be effective, presentation needs to be simple, clear and short. The accompanying handout can then be more elaborate in conveying the detail\r\nHand out may be used:\r\n1. To indicate aims and objectives of the session\r\n2. To summarize the key points of a presentation\r\n3. To  convey the instruction for an exercise which is to follow\r\n4. To provide illustrations and examples of material discussed in the main presentation\r\n5. To provide supplementary information which, is not contained in the main presentation\r\n6. To provide a direction to background reading and other self-directed learning material when appropriate\r\n\r\nTypes-2 types\r\n Comprehensive hand out\r\n Skeletal hand out\r\nComprehensive hand out- avoid the need to take extensive notes but encourage lack of concentration\r\nSkeletal hand out- encourages active learning\r\nFollowing points may be regarded as tips in the preparation of hand out\r\n- Avoid lengthy hand out and too much detail\r\n- Avoid unnecessary jargons or abbreviations.\r\n- Use pictures, charts and diagrams to convey ideas whenever possible\r\n- Use larger print sizes and good spacing of text to aid reading\r\n\r\n \r\nNow skeletal handouts of my lecture on “Urinary tract infection (UTI)”.\r\n      \r\n Objective:\r\n                  Definition of UTI\r\n                  Common organisms\r\n                  Pathophysiology\r\n                  Diagnosis\r\n                  Management\r\n                  Prognosis\r\n\r\n\r\nDefinition:\r\n              Invasion and multiplication of micro-organism in the urinary system\r\n              -any component of the urinary tract including\r\n             -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ---------------\r\n\r\n             ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n            -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nEtiology\r\nCommonest organism Escherichia coli others\r\n  \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n\r\nCommon clinical clues\r\nSymptoms-\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSigns-\r\nGeneral exam-\r\nTemperature------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nRenal angle\r\nPathophysiology\r\n3 routes of entry\r\n------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\r\nDiagnosis-\r\nUrine--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nBlood--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nManagement-\r\nGeneral measures----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\n\r\nAntibiotics---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nPrognosis------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n\r\nCase-\r\nA 30-year-old lady presented with 3-day history of increased urinary frequency, dysuria and mild supra-pubic tenderness.\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat may be organisms?\r\n\r\nWhat clinical sign you look for?\r\n\r\nHow will you confirm?\r\n\r\nHow will you treat?\r\n\r\nEvaluation of the teaching-learning session and feedback\r\n1. Definition of UTI\r\n2. Etiology of UTI\r\n3. Evaluation: clinical and lab\r\n4. Principles of management of UTI\r\n5. Prognosis of UTI\r\n\r\nFurther reading\r\nGoddard J, Turner AN, Cumming AD, Stewart LH. Kidney and urinary tract disease. In: Colledge NR, Walker BR, Ralston SH, editors. Davidsons Principles & Practices of Medicine. 21st ed. London. Churchill Livingstone 205; p 455-71.\r\n\r\n', '2018-03-09 01:30:42', 'upload/attachment/2c3fcad564beb4e4cd178f6c91711a04.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
