INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (194, 137, 'Skeletal Handouts of a Lecture on ‘’Tetanus’', 'Title: Skeletal Handouts of a Lecture on ‘’Tetanus’\r\nI. Introduction: \r\nLet me say a story of a “construction worker” who received a deep penetrating wound in his sole of the right foot with a dirty nail……………..\r\nWhat do you think about the disease of this gentleman? \r\nOur today’s topic is “Tetanus” \r\nPrerequisite knowledge on Clostridium tetani – causative organism of Tetanus. \r\n• General character- spore bearing, anerobic rods \r\n• Habitat\r\n• Culture character\r\n• Viability- spores remain viable almost indefinitely, killed by moist heat 121ᵒ C for 20 minutes, Penicillin \r\n• Toxins and enzymes- Tetanospasmins, very powerful neurotoxin \r\n• Antigenicity \r\nPathogenicity – causes Tetanus in human\r\nObjectives\r\n• To understand the disease process of Tetanus \r\n• To be able to examine and diagnose a case of Tetanus\r\n• To be able to treat a case of Tetanus \r\n• To learn the importance of prophylaxis for Tetanus\r\nKey Points \r\nClostridium tetani, spores, susceptible wounds, neurotoxins, latent tetanus, acetylcholine, neuromuscular junction, lock jaw, risus sardonicus, opisthotonus, human anti tetanus globulin, penicillin, metronidazole\r\n\r\nII. Tetanus:\r\nNeurotoxic disease caused by exotoxin of Cl. tetani at the site of infection in a susceptible wound in human \r\nPrevalence\r\nSusceptible wounds \r\nSource of organism\r\nIncubation period \r\nEvolution of the disease – Tetanospasmin inhibits cholinesterase at motor end plates, and excess of acetylcholine locally causes tonic muscle spasm, travels along nerves to CNS to cause explosive and wide spread reflex muscle spasm. \r\nPeriod of onset/incubation period\r\nLatent tetani\r\nSymptoms- dysphagia, jaw stiffness, severe pain in neck, back, abdomen etc. \r\nSigns – Tonic muscle spasm, sardonic smile, respiratory and swallowing difficulty, reflex convulsion- opisthotonus, respiratory failure and death\r\n\r\nDifferential Diagnosis\r\nTreatment –      Human anti tetanus globulin/tetanus anti toxin\r\n Tetanus toxoid \r\n Antibiotics – Penicillin and Metronidazole\r\n General measures- stage 1 (Mild cases), stage 2 (severely ill), stage 3 (dangerously ill)\r\n Care of the wound \r\nPrognosis \r\nProphylaxis – immunization\r\n Childhood \r\n Maternal \r\n After inflicting susceptible wound \r\n- Antibiotic \r\n- Care of the wound\r\nQuestions – why the organism is dangerous?\r\n- Why the disease is serious?\r\n- Tell about the effective preventive measures.\r\nDoes anybody have any question?\r\n\r\nIII. Conclusion: \r\nSummary- gm+ve anerobic spore bearing Cl. tetani causes tetanus through its powerful neurotoxin by blocking acetylcholine metabolism at motor end plate of skeletal muscles leading to local and generalized muscles spasm to death. Prophylaxis is effective and preferred. Treatment is difficult and expensive. Prognosis is gloomy. \r\nTake home message- ubiquity of Cl. tetani render tetanus eradication impossible, but it is vaccine preventable disease. Universal active immunization against tetanus should be adopted. \r\nFurther reading- Text book……………….\r\n           Tetanus CDC\r\n           Tetanus WHO\r\n           Web-based reading \r\nImportant points to be noted (by students)\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-03-10 12:07:12', 'upload/attachment/3cb2fbc7176db01537446f682eb60912.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
