INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (204, 163, 'Prepare a study guide of a topic of your discipline incorporating the following headings i. Learning objectives ii. Introduction iii. Teaching-learning methods iv. Learning materials v. Self-assessment exercise ( Two MCQs ) ', 'Module: 2 Instructional design\r\nUnit: IMD4 study guide and handout\r\nFellow ID: 181020\r\n\r\nTitle: Concepts of Digestion and Absorption of Carbohydrate\r\n\r\n1. learning objectives \r\nAt the end of the session the students will be able to:\r\na) Define digestion\r\nb) Name the dietary carbohydrates\r\nc) List the enzymes of carbohydrate digestion\r\nd) Mention the sources of enzymes of carbohydrate digestion \r\ne) Describe the steps of carbohydrate digestion \r\nf) Name the end products of carbohydrate digestion\r\ng) Define absorption\r\nh) Enumerate the Process of carbohydrate absorption\r\n                              \r\n2. Introduction:\r\nWe get nutrients from outside through diet and the gastrointestinal tract is the portal through which these nutrients enter the body. Most of the nutrients present in food are in more complex  form which are not suitable to enter the body. In the digestive tract, these more complex macronutrients are broken down into suitable absorbable form. Conversion of complex macronutrients into suitable absorbable form is called digestion. Basic changes occur in digestion are softening, lubricating and hydrolysis of food particles and digestion occurs in different parts of alimentary tract. For this purpose, two basic requirements are digestive juices and movements of alimentary tract. \r\nMajor carbohydrates in ordinary diet are starch, cellulose (Dietary fibers), sucrose, lactose. Carbohydrate digestion starts in mouth. Starch is digested by salivary α amylase and pancreatic α amylase into maltose, maltotriose and α limit dextrin. In small intestine, these maltose, maltotriose and α limit dextrin are digested by maltase and α limit dextrinase into glucose. Sucrose and lactose are digested by sucrase and lactase in small intestine to produce glucose, fructose and galactose. Cellulose is not digested in our body. But it acts as dietary fibers.\r\n\r\nThese end products of digestion pass through the intestinal mucosa and enter into the circulation by the process, which is called absorption. Absorption of glucose, fructose, galactose occur in duodenum and upper jejunum by different types of transport systems. Glucose and galactose are transported from lumen to enterocyte by -Secondary active transport (Na glucose/ galactose co-transport). Then they are transported from enterocyte to circulation by- Facilitated diffusion. Fructose is absorbed by –Facilitated diffusion.\r\n\r\n\r\n3. Teaching-learning methods:\r\na) Face to face interactive lecture on study guide for whole group at the Medical college\r\nb) Small group teaching by tutorial, practical and assignments\r\nc) Self-learning and group discussion by reading selective chapters from books, lectures, articles, journals and websites\r\n\r\n4. Learning materials\r\na. Books-\r\ni. Review of Medical Physiology by William F. Ganong, 21st edition, section-5 (Gastrointestinal Functions), chapter -25, pg471-475.\r\nii. Text book of Medical Physiology by Guyton & Hall, 11th edition, chapter- 65 pg 808-809.\r\niii.  Lippincott Illustrated Reviews Biochemistry, 7th edition, chapter-7, pg 86-89\r\n\r\n b. Articles- \r\ni.  Levin R J. Digestion and absorption of carbohydrates— from molecules and membranes to humans.The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition 1994; 59(3): 690–698\r\n\r\nc. Website-\r\n            i.   https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LWfXeCVp7Wk \r\n              ii.   https://doi.org/10.1093/ajcn/59.3.690S\r\n\r\n\r\n5. Self-assessment exercise-\r\n\r\nPut ‘T’ for True and ‘F’ for False on left side of each stem\r\n1. Choose the correct answer regarding digestion of carbohydrate- \r\na) It begins in mouth\r\nb) Pancreatic α amylase acts on α 1-6 glycosidic bond of starch\r\nc) Intestinal oligosaccharidases act on starch\r\nd) ‘Lactose intolerance’ is due to deficiency of lactase\r\ne) End products are glucose, fructose and galactose\r\n\r\n2. Choose the correct answer regarding absorption of carbohydrate-\r\na) Sites of absorption are mainly duodenum and upper jejunum\r\nb) Fructose is absorbed by facilitated diffusion\r\nc) Glucose is absorbed by simple diffusion\r\nd) SGLT1 remains in basolateral membrane\r\ne) GLUT5 remains in luminal membrane\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-03-15 09:01:06', 'upload/attachment/19d8fdcb39d018913b944869886238cd.doc', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
