INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (214, 157, 'A Study Guide on a Topic of Surgical Discipline “Burn”', 'I. Learning Objectives\r\nAfter completion of the session students will be able:\r\na) To define and classify burns\r\nb) To assess the area and depth of burns\r\nc) To understand the methods of calculating the quantity and rate of fluid to be infused\r\nd) To understand the technics for treating burned area and the patient \r\ne) To understand the pathophysiology of electrical and chemical burns\r\n\r\nII. Introduction \r\nThe incidents of burn injury varies greatly between cultures. In United Kingdom, 175,000 (of 65 million population), in United States 2 million (of 250 million) and in Australia-Newzeland 1% of population attend accident and emergency departments suffering from burns. About 50% of those suffer from daily living activity restriction, 10% require hospitalization and 10% of those hospitalized suffer with burns of sufficient severity to threaten life. Half of the victims are under 16 years of age. Some burns occur as genuine accidents but most are caused by carelessness, inattention, pre-existing medical conditions or follow alcohol or drug abuse. Most electrical and chemical injuries occur in adults. Cold and radiation injuries are very rare causes of burn. \r\nIn Bangladesh, the incidence of burn injury (though not accurate data) is approximately 3 million (of 120 million-in 2012) which is much higher than developed countries, largely due to poor electrical installations and open fire cooking, heating and smoking in households. \r\nLegislation, health promotion, appliance design regulation regarding flammable clothes and furniture, promotion of smoke alarm, education of parents etc. can reduce the incidence of burns.\r\nA large injury has a significant impact on patient, family, friends and patient’s future. Burned patients are managed initially like any other trauma patients (A, B, C, D……of ATLS). Estimation of area and depth of burn and estimation of fluid requirements is crucial in early management of burns. Multidisciplinary approach is needed for adequate and effective care of the burned patients. Better understanding of the control of physiology along with improvements in reconstruction and rehabilitation services will provide a better future for burned victims. \r\nIII. Teaching Learning Methods\r\na) Face-to-face interactive lecture on burn for third-year students in a lecture hall of Ibrahim Medical college.\r\nb) Tutorials for small groups on assessment of area of burn, methods of calculation of fluid requirement, exercise on first aid and emergency management of burned patients (ATLS) etc. \r\nc) Bed-side teaching on burn wound care, complications of burn like post-burn contracture, keloids, marjolin’s ulcer etc. \r\nd) Individualized learning; reading selective chapters from books, articles, journals, and websites. \r\nIV. Learning Materials \r\na) Books\r\ni. Bailey and Love’s Short Practice of Surgery, edited by Norman S. Williams, Christopher J.K. Bulstrode, P. Ronan O’Connell, 26th edition, part 4 (Trauma, Chapter 31 (Burn)), pg 385 to 400. \r\nii. Current Surgical Diagnosis and Treatment by Lawrence W. Way, 11th edition, Chapter 15 (Burns and Other Thermal Injuries), pg 267 to 281. \r\nb) Articles\r\nStewart J. Bishop RB. Recent Trends in Assessment and Management of Burns. Journal of the International Society for Burn Injuries 2017; vol 9(2); 67-69.  \r\n\r\nV. Self-Assessment Exercise (MCQ)\r\na) All the cases of burn listed below should ideally be treated in a specialized Burn Unit except-\r\ni. Burns requiring fluid resuscitation \r\nii. Circumferrential limb or chest burn \r\niii. 12% partial thickness burn in a young lady\r\niv. Burns in children or the elderly\r\nv. Electrical burns \r\nb) Late complications of burns include the following- \r\ni. Curling’s ulcer\r\nii. Cushing’s ulcer\r\niii. Protein loosing enteropathy \r\niv. Immunodeficiency \r\nv. Marjolin’s ulcer\r\n\r\n', 