INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (221, 186, 'Principle of effective teaching and learning', 'A)  Definition of Teaching & Learning\r\nTeaching-\r\n      Teaching is an interactive process as well as an intentional activity that provides opportunities for students to learn.\r\n       Teaching is interaction involving teacher, student and tasks. Purpose of teaching is to facilitate learning. \r\nLearning-\r\n     Learning is a constructive & active process that results in change in behavior and some modification in way of thinking, feeling & doing.\r\n       Learning is an experience that generates many things like- skills, insight, appreciation, attitudes and feeling toward self, others, learning and life itself.  \r\nB)  Strategies to enhance effective learning\r\nStrategies that research indicates can be very effective in helping struggling learners to successfully master new academic skills:\r\n• 1. Instructional Match. We have to ensure that students are being taught at the optimal instructional level, one that challenges them but provides enough success to keep these students confident and invested in learning.\r\n• 2. Scaffolding. We have to provide \'scaffolding\' support (individual instructional modifications) to students as necessary to help them to master a new task or keep up with more advanced learners. Examples of scaffolding strategies include reducing the number of problems assigned to a student, permitting the student to use technological aids (e.g., word processing software which predicts student word selection to reduce keyboarding), and using cooperative learning groups that pool the group\'s knowledge to complete assignments.\r\n• 3. Step-by-Step Strategies. For complex, conceptually difficult, or multi-step academic operations, we have to break these operations down into simple steps & teach students to use the steps. \r\n• 4. Modeling & Demonstration. We have to model and demonstrate explicit strategies to students for learning academic material or completing assignments. Have them use these strategies under supervision until we are sure that students understand and can correctly use them.\r\n• 5. Performance Feedback. Make sure that students who are mastering new academic skills have frequent opportunities to try these skills out with immediate corrective feedback and encouragement. Prompt guidance and feedback will prevent students from accidentally \'learning\' how to perform a skill incorrectly!\r\n• 6. Opportunities to Drill & Practice to Strengthen Fragile Skills. As students become more proficient in their new skills and can work independently, give them lots of opportunities to drill and practice to strengthen the skills. Whenever possible, make student practice sessions interesting by using game-like activities; coming up with real-world, applied assignments; or incorporating themes or topics that the student finds interesting.\r\n• 7. Student \'Talk-Through\' Activities. When students appear to have successfully learned a skill, set up activities for them to complete and ask the students to \'talk\' you through the activity (i.e., announce each step that they are taking, describe their problem-solving strategies aloud, describe any road-blocks that they run into and tell you how they will go about solving them, etc.).\r\n• 8. Periodic Review. Once students have mastered a particular academic skill, the instructor will quickly move them on to a more advanced learning objective. However, as teacher we should make sure that students retain previously mastered academic skills by periodically having them review that material. \r\n• 9. Progress Monitoring. Teachers can verify that students are making appropriate learning progress only when they are able to measure that progress on a regular basis. The instructor may want to consider information from several assessment approaches to monitor student progress: e.g., curriculum-based assessment, accuracy and completeness of student assignments, student \'talk-through\' demonstrations of problem-solving, etc.\r\nIn other words there are 6 principles of teaching characteristics that facilitate learning-\r\n1. Interest and explanation\r\n2. Concern and respect for students and student learning\r\n3. Appropriate assessment and feedback\r\n4. Clear goals and intellectual challenge\r\n5. Independence, control and active engagement\r\n6. Learning from students\r\n\r\nStrategies for learning from learner’s perspectives are-\r\n• Attending class. \r\n• Reading books. \r\n• Writing \r\n• Examining patient.\r\n• Discussion with peers\r\n\r\nC)   Conditions of Learning\r\n      An atmosphere or conditions to facilitate learning are learning environment which-\r\n• Encourages people to be Active\r\n• Emphasize the personal nature of  learning\r\n• Accept that difference is desirable.\r\n• Recognize the people’s right to make mistake.\r\n• Tolerates imperceptions.\r\n• Encourages openness of self & trust in self\r\n• Makes people feel respected & accepted.\r\n• Facilitates discovery.\r\n• Puts emphasis on self-evaluation & cooperation.\r\n• Permits confrontation.\r\n\r\n\r\nD)  Roles of a teacher\r\n         12 roles of the medical teacher, adapted from Harden, R.M & Crosby, J (2000)  \r\nFacilitator-\r\n                1.  Mentor\r\n2. Learning facilitator \r\n\r\nRole model- \r\n3. On-the-job role model\r\n4.  Teaching role modeling                     \r\nInformation provider- \r\n5. Lecturer\r\n6. Clinical & practical teacher\r\n\r\n\r\nResource developer- \r\n7. Research\r\n8. Learning environment\r\nPlanner-\r\n9. Course & experience organizer\r\n10. Curriculum planner\r\nAssessor- \r\n11. Curriculum evaluator\r\n12.  Student assessor\r\n\r\n\r\nE) Types of clinical teaching\r\n• Bed side teaching, \r\n• Teaching in clinical skill center \r\n• Ambulatory care teaching.  \r\nF) Educational objectives that can be achieved in bed side teaching-\r\nPossible Goals of Clinical Teaching  McLeod and Harden (1985) -\r\n• Clinical skill- Perform complete and orderly physical examinations\r\n• Communication skill- Communicate information reliably\r\n• Clinical reasoning- Solve scientific and professional problems \r\n• Perform skills procedures- Practical procedure: CV line, CPR, Venipuncture, catheterization.\r\n• Patient investigation & management- Accumulate factual healthcare knowledge \r\n• Data interpretation& retrieval- Accumulate and record information about patients, Interpret data\r\n• Professional skill- role model for professional behavior.\r\n• Attitude & ethics- Develop appropriate attitudes to patients and allied health care workers, Acquire positive attitudes to independent learning \r\n• Develop familiarity with health care services and facilities \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n1. http://www.interventioncentral.org/academic-interventions/general-academic/teacher-strategies-promote-learning \r\n2. http://medschool.ucla.edu/workfiles/site-GME/CurrentResidents/MedicalTeacher.pdf \r\n3. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n4. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition.\r\n5. Ramsden, P. (1992). Learning to Teach in Higher Education. New York: Routledge. \r\n6. http://www.faculty.londondeanery.ac.uk/e-learning/explore-further/teaching_and_learning_at_the_bedside.pdf \r\n', '2018-03-28 06:57:53', 'upload/attachment/8ac03e8d0f00934f04d314e7de3d1e66.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (222, 174, 'Teaching and learning ', '', '2018-03-29 01:14:36', 'upload/attachment/61327ed1ed1917dcdbc89d6fac4c8ada.pdf', '<p>Dear fellow.</p><p>Thanks for your effort to prepare this assignment works.  But you need to rewrite assignment as per my feedback and  send back  at or before tomorrow night.  Following are my observation:</p><ul><li>\'For effective learning main role is played by teacher\'.....This statement demand further study to clear  your understanding regarding  teaching -learning. Learning is an active and constructive process, the <b>main role should played by the learner</b> not by the teacher. Teacher only can facilitate learning. The main role of teacher is to create an environment/ atmosphere where the learner actively engaged to practice the learning process.</li><li>Learning strategies are those strategies that encourage to active participation of the learner and the learning atmosphere are the environment  for learning process.</li><li>Types/ situations of clinical teaching are <b>Bed site teaching</b>,<b>Ambulatory care</b>/OPD,<b>Skill learning center</b> and <b>Community based.</b></li><li>Learning objectives of BST: such as<b> </b>clinical reasoning, communication skill, practical procedure, attitude.</li><li>Role of teacher: 12 roles of a teacher.</li></ul><p>You please go through the books of harden(Practical guide for Medical teacher) & prof Tahmina Begum(Concept of medical education). </p><p>Please feel free for any query.</p><p> Thanks</p><p>Prof Md Shah Alam</p><p>MBBS, DTCD, MCPS, MMEd</p><p>Prof & Head, Forensic Medicine</p><p>Ibrahim Medical college</p>', NULL, '2018-04-01 14:32:26', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (223, 179, 'Define teaching & learning. Enumerate the strategies that will enhance effective learning and enlist the conditions of learning. Enlist the roles of a teacher. What are the types of clinical teaching? Describe the educational objectives that can be achiev', 'Dr. Md. Towhidur Rahman\r\nName of assignment: Define teaching & learning. Enumerate the strategies that will enhance effective learning and enlist the conditions of learning. Enlist the roles of a teacher. What are the types of clinical teaching? Describe the educational objectives that can be achieved in bed side teaching.\r\n\r\nTeaching: \r\nIntentional activity & interaction between teacher, student & task under teacher responsibility in order to bring about expected change in the student behavior.\r\nLearning:\r\nContinuous process resulting in some modification relatively permanent of the behavior, in the way of thinking, feeling & doing of the learner.\r\nStrategies will enhance effective learning:\r\nStrategies for learning-\r\nA. Attending class. \r\nB. Reading books. \r\nC. Writing \r\nD. Examining patient\r\nE. Discussion with peers\r\n9 Strategies for fostering deep approach\r\nExtent to which this strategy embody: motivational context, learner activity, interaction with others & well-structured knowledge base.\r\nStrategy-1: Independent learning\r\nStrategy-2: Personal development\r\nStrategy-3: Problem based learning\r\nStrategy-4: Reflection\r\nStrategy-5: Independent group work\r\nStrategy-6: Learning by doing (experiment)\r\nStrategy-7: Developing learning skills\r\nStrategy-8: Project works\r\nStrategy-9: Fine tuning\r\nConditions of learning:\r\nAn atmosphere which -\r\n Encourages people to be active\r\n Emphasize the personal nature of  learning\r\n Accept that difference is desirable\r\n Recognize the people’s right to make mistake\r\n Tolerates Imperceptions\r\n Encourages openness of self & trust in self\r\n Makes people feel respected & accepted\r\n Facilitates discovery\r\n Puts emphasis on self-evaluation & cooperation\r\n Permits Confrontation\r\nRoles of teacher: \r\n12 roles of a teacher -\r\n1. Information provider\r\n• Lecturer\r\n• Clinical/practical teaching\r\n2. Role model\r\n• Role model (teaching)\r\n• Role model (job)\r\n3. Facilitator\r\n• Mentor\r\n• Learning facilitator\r\n4. Assessor\r\n• Student assessor\r\n• Curriculum evaluator\r\n5. Planner\r\n• Curriculum planner\r\n• Course organizer\r\n6. Resource provider\r\n• Resource provider\r\n• Study guide\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTypes of clinical teaching:\r\nTeaching-learning involving patient & their problems.\r\nThree types:\r\n1. Bed side teaching \r\nLearning triad involving patient, student & tutor in which teacher-student interaction & active participation of the students.\r\n2. Teaching in clinical skill center\r\nClinical skill center seeks to provide an environment for learning clinical skills in which students can practice without jeopardizing patient care or provoking adverse comment.\r\n3. Ambulatory care teaching\r\nIt offers a variety of clinical situations & a range of common clinical conditions not seen in inpatient care and patient seen in an environment more closely resembling their home situation & more closely linked with primary care.\r\n\r\nEducational objectives in bed side teaching:\r\n1. Clinical skills – For junior students opportunities to become proficient at normal physical examination while senior students gain practice in eliciting abnormal physical signs.\r\n2. Communication skill – Many opportunities exist for students to practice communication skill.\r\n3. Clinical reasoning – Students can observe this in practice by junior & senior staff.\r\n4. Practical procedures – CV line, CPR, Venipuncture, catheterization.\r\n5. Patient investigation & management – Many opportunities for students to observe & discuss aspects of both of these.\r\n6. Data interpretation and retrieval – Interpretation of laboratory reports & accessing scientific papers for reference are examples.\r\n7. Professional skills – Role model for professional behavior in which junior & senior doctors in their working relationship with other healthcare professionals.\r\n8. Transferrable skills – Many of the abilities acquired in the ward setting will be of value in other doctor-patient situations.\r\n9. Attitude & ethics – Appropriate attitudes & ethics can be observed by the students in their ward attachments.\r\n', '2018-03-29 05:19:41', 'upload/attachment/d0bd7bd850e03a64bad5c042063f3c54.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (224, 183, 'Principles of Teaching and Learning and Teaching Methods', 'Define teaching & learning. Enumerate the strategies that will enhance effective learning and enlist the conditions of learning. Enlist the roles of a teacher. What are the types of clinical teaching? Describe the educational objectives that can be achieved in bed side teaching.\r\n', '2018-03-29 07:05:39', 'upload/attachment/e07a04393f4677378e206e3368e35935.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (225, 178, 'Define teaching & learning. Enumerate the strategies that will enhance effective learning and enlist the conditions of learning. Enlist the roles of a teacher. What are the types of clinical teaching? Describe the educational objectives that can be achiev', 'Module: 3 Teaching-learning\r\nUnit: M3TL1 “Principles of teaching and learning and teaching methods”\r\nFellow ID: 181020\r\n\r\nTeaching-\r\nTeaching is the process of attending people’s needs, experiences and feelings, and making specific interventions to help them to learn particular things. \r\nLearning-\r\nLearning is the constructive and active process of acquiring new or modifying existing knowledge, behaviors, skills, values, or preferences and cause relatively permanent change in behavior through experience, instruction, or study. \r\n\r\nThe strategies that will enhance effective learning-\r\nThe manner in which a student studies and absorbs information can have an important impact on their education. Studying habits are skills that can be improved throughout a person\'s life by the application of effective learning techniques and strategies. \r\nThe different strategies are-\r\n• Attending classes\r\n• Reading books\r\n• Examining patients\r\n• Project works\r\n• Problem based learning\r\n• Independent group works\r\n• Discussion with peers\r\nTeachers need to integrate learning strategies into teaching which can help students to learn the skills, which include-\r\n• How to learn in a class, take notes, provide answers, use hand outs\r\n• How to work effectively in a group\r\n• How to engage in a discussion\r\n• How to find information\r\nBy these strategies, they can develop independent learning and personal skills.\r\n\r\nConditions of learning-\r\nLearning situation has two parts- one internal (capabilities that already exists in learner before new learning starts) to the learner and the other external (different stimulus exist outside the learner) to the person. The relationship between the two parts and the behavior change are called the conditions of learning.\r\nSo, the conditions of learning are-\r\n• Clearly defined objectives\r\n• Scope of active participation\r\n• Scope of frequent brief practice\r\n• Specific feedback to identify error\r\n• Reinforcing practice of correct elements\r\n• Study skill and learn how to learn\r\n• Fostering deep approaches\r\n\r\nRoles of a teacher-\r\nTeacher plays a very important role in teaching and learning that supports students to acquire and apply knowledge and skills. \r\nRoles of a teacher are-\r\n• Information provider- teachers identify and articulate clear learning objective and provide instruction through large group teaching like lectures, small group teaching like clinical and practical teaching or individual teaching.\r\n• Role model- teachers may be a role model to the students by their teaching qualities.\r\n• Facilitators- they act as mentor and facilitator by providing relevant and continuous feedback and supporting learner to be an independent learner.\r\n• Assessor- teachers assess prior learning by using a variety of assessment tools and evaluate assessment data and take required steps. They also evaluate curriculum.\r\n• Planner- they play important role in planning curriculum, selecting objectives and organizing course.\r\n• Resource provider- They also provide resource and study guide.\r\n\r\nTypes of clinical teaching-\r\nClinical teaching is teaching which takes place in a clinical context. It usually involves teachers, learners and patients and clinical procedures, and as such, necessitates sensitivity, confidentiality and discretion. \r\nThere are three types of clinical teaching-\r\n• Bed side teaching\r\n• Teaching in clinical skill center\r\n• Ambulatory care teaching\r\nBed side teaching-\r\nIt is a special type of small group teaching in presence of patient. A clinical teacher and a group of learners see a patient, listen to the history (from patient or learner), elicit or verify physical signs, discuss provisional diagnosis, diagnostic or therapeutic options. \r\nDuring this the teacher will observe learners’ patient interactions and their thinking skills. It is a rich visual, auditory, tactile & olfactory experience.\r\nTeaching in clinical skill center-\r\nThe clinical skills center was developed to teach and assess the clinical skills of medical students, residents and physicians in an environment that simulates the clinical settings. The center is used for both teaching and assessing clinical communication and physical exam skills, and it will be the site in which students take their multi-station Objective Structured Clinical Exams (OSCEs).  Faculty will also use the center to develop clinical teaching skills.\r\nAmbulatory care teaching-\r\nAmbulatory care refers to medical services performed on an outpatient basis, without admission to a hospital or other facility. Ambulatory care is provided in settings such as dialysis clinics, ambulatory surgical centers, hospital outpatient departments, and the offices of physicians and other health professionals. Here student- patient interaction takes place in a non threatening environment.\r\n\r\nEducational objectives that can be achieved in bed side teaching-\r\n• Clinical skills- Junior students get opportunities to learn history taking and become efficient in normal physical examination while more senior students gain practice in eliciting abnormal physical signs.\r\n• Communication skill- Students get many opportunities to practice and achieve Communication skill.\r\n• Clinical reasoning- Students can observe this in practice by junior and senior staff.\r\n• Practical procedures- Venipuncture, Bladder catheterization, CPR, CV line, which are readily available on most wards for student’s to practice.\r\n• Patient investigation and management- There are many opportunities for students to observe and discuss both investigation and management of patients.\r\n• Data interpretation and retrieval- Students get chance to interpret the laboratory reports and access scientific papers for reference.\r\n• Professional skills- The observation of both junior and senior doctors in their working relationship with other healthcare professionals help students to develop role models for Professional behavior.\r\n• Transferable skills- Many of the abilities acquired in ward settings are valued in other doctor-patient relationship.\r\n• Attitude and ethics- Appropriate attitudes and ethics can be achieved by the students in their ward attachments.\r\nWhen these objectives are achieved, learners experience an interaction of theoretical, practical knowledges in context of patient which guide them throughout their professional life.\r\n', '2018-03-30 01:43:38', 'upload/attachment/e5360c2bd08633fa1a8f54ce9653d312.doc', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
