INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (235, 182, 'Define Teaching and Learning ', 'Define Teaching and Learning\r\nTeaching\r\nMay be defined as an organized communication between the teacher and the students providing opportunities to learn\r\nInteraction between teacher and student under teacher’s responsibility in order to bring about expected change in the students’ behavior\r\nAn interactive process as well as intentional activity concerned with learning with the student\r\nCreating learning experience to build, develop and nurture thinking abilities \r\nExchange of ideas as well as imparting information\r\nLearning\r\nMay be defined as change of behavior or capacity to new behavior\r\nSimply acquiring knowledge by study\r\nA process resulting in some modification relatively permanent of the behavior, in the way of thinking, feeling and doing of the learner\r\nConstructive and active process that result in change in behavior\r\nTaking new information, build it on existing knowledge\r\nEstablishing connection within and between units of knowledge\r\nAn evolutionary process, cooperative and collaborative, unique and individual, primarily controlled by the learner, affected by the total state of learner \r\nA consequence of an experience, not directly observable\r\n\r\nStrategies that will enhance effective learning\r\n• Objectives are clearly defined\r\n• Scope for active participation\r\n• Scope for frequent brief practice\r\n• Specific feedback to identify error\r\n• Reinforcing practice of correct elements\r\n• Study skill and learning how to learn\r\n• Fostering deep approach (9 strategies)\r\nStrategy-1: Independent learning\r\nStrategy-2: Personal development\r\nStrategy-3: Problem based learning\r\nStrategy-4: Reflection\r\nStrategy-5: Independent group work\r\nStrategy-6: Learning by doing (experimental)\r\nStrategy-7: Developing learning skills\r\nStrategy-8: Project works\r\nStrategy-9: Fine tuning\r\n• Six powerful learning strategies\r\n1. Spacing – spaced practice/ spiraling – review\r\n2. Retrieval practice\r\n3. Elaboration – with open ended questions by self/ facilitator\r\n4. Interleaving – a skill is learned more effectively if mix practice of it with other skills\r\n5. Concrete examples\r\n6. Dual coding – text with visuals (image, chart, graph, graphic organizer, diagram, sketch etc.)\r\n\r\nConditions of Learning\r\nDifferent internal and external conditions are necessary for each type of learning. For example –\r\nFor cognitive strategies – a chance to practice developing new solutions of problems.\r\nFor attitude – exposed to a credible role model or persuasive arguments \r\nFor intellectual skill - stimulus recognition/ classical conditioning \r\nresponse generation in operant conditioning \r\nchaining/ procedure following – complex operant conditioning\r\nverbal association – use of terminology\r\ndiscrimination – learning of responding different to different stimuli\r\nconcept formation – learning a general response to a class of stimuli\r\nrule application – a rule is a chain of two or more concepts \r\nproblem solving – application of previously learned rules and concepts to new situation\r\nConditions of learning (R.Gagne) outlines 9 instructional events and corresponding cognitive processes: mental conditions for learning\r\n1. Gain attention – stimuli activates receptors\r\n2. Inform learners of objectives – creates level of expectation for learning \r\n3. Stimulate recall prior learning – retrieval on activation of short term memory\r\n4. Present the content – selective perception of content\r\n5. Provide “learning guidance” – semantic encoding for storage long term memory\r\n6. Elicit performance (practice) – response to questions to enhance encoding and verification\r\n7. Provide feedback – reinforcement and assessment of correct performance\r\n8. Asses performance – retrieval and reinforcement of content as final evaluation\r\n9. Enhance retention and transfer to the job – retrieval and generalization of learned skill to new situation\r\nConditions to facilitate learning – an atmosphere which \r\n encourages people to be active\r\n emphasize the personal nature of learning\r\n accept that difference is desirable\r\n recognize the people’s right to mistake\r\n tolerates interceptions\r\n encourage openness of self and trust in self\r\n makes people feel respected and accepted\r\n facilitates discovery\r\n puts emphasis on self-evaluation and cooperation\r\n permits confrontation\r\n\r\n\r\nRoles of a teacher\r\nThere are six areas of activity of the teacher. Each of the six areas can be subdivided into two roles, making a total of twelve roles. Some roles are associated with face to face contact with students while others are associated with less student contact. Some roles require more content expertise and some require more educational expertise. The twelve educational roles are:\r\n Information provider – \r\n1. Lecturer in classroom setting \r\n2. Teacher in clinical or practical class setting\r\nRole model – \r\n3. On-the-job role model (eg. in clinics, ward rounds etc.)\r\n4. Role model in the teaching setting\r\nFacilitator – \r\n5. Mentor, personal advisor or tutor to a student or group of students\r\n6. Learning facilitator (eg. Supporting students’ learning in a problem based learning small group in the laboratory, in the integrated practical class session or in the clinical setting) \r\nExaminer – \r\n7. Planning or participating in formal examinations of students\r\n8. Curriculum evaluator – evaluation of the teaching program and the teachers\r\nPlanner – \r\n9. Curriculum planner, participating in overall planning of the curriculum, through for example, curriculum planning committees such as Undergraduate Medical Education Committee\r\n10.  Course organizer, responsibility for planning and implementing a specific course within the curriculum. This may for example relate to one system or one theme or to a special study module\r\nResource developer – \r\n11.  Production of study guide to support the students’ learning in the course\r\n12.  Developing learning resource materials in the form of computer programs, video tapes or print which can be used as adjuncts to the lecture or other sessions  \r\nOther roles for the teacher include \r\n• Clinical\r\n• Administrative\r\n• Research\r\n• Develop a positive, respectful working relationship\r\n• Provide the teacher assistants with the requisite information \r\n• Reports to parents\r\na. Informal, ongoing\r\nb. Formal, written reports\r\n• Maintain records\r\n• Developing supportive environment for learners\r\nEach teacher need not have all the roles. Some teachers will have only one role while most teachers will have several roles. All roles, however, need to be represented in an institute or teaching organization.\r\n\r\nTypes of Clinical Teaching\r\nTeaching learning involving patients and their problems. \r\n• Bedside teaching\r\n• Teaching in clinical skill center\r\n• Ambulatory care teaching\r\n• Case method \r\n• Process recording\r\n• Individual conference\r\n• Group conference\r\n• Teaching rounds\r\n• Assignments\r\n• Role play\r\n• Field trip\r\n• Teaching in protected time\r\n• Teaching in out-patients\r\n• Teaching in general practice \r\n• Teaching on call in A&E\r\n• Teaching in the theatre room\r\n\r\nEducational objectives that can be achieved in the bedside teaching\r\n• Clinical skills: \r\nFor junior students – opportunities to become proficient at normal physical examinations\r\nFor more senior students – opportunities in eliciting abnormal physical signs\r\n• Communication skills\r\n• Clinical reasoning: students can observe this in practice by junior and senior staff\r\n• Practical procedures: \r\n1. Venipuncture\r\n2. Bladder catheterization\r\n3. Cannulation of a peripheral vein\r\n4. Central venous line\r\n5. Cardio-pulmonary resuscitation\r\n• Patient investigation and management: opportunities for students to observe and discuss aspects of both of these\r\n• Data interpretation and retrieval: interpretation of laboratory reports and assessing scientific papers for reference \r\n• Professional skills\r\no Observation of both junior and senior doctors in their working relationship with other healthcare professionals help students develop role models for professional behavior\r\n• Transferable skills \r\n• Attitude and ethics: Attitude and ethics towards patients and attending healthcare workers \r\n• Develop familiarity with healthcare services and facilities\r\n• Accumulate factual healthcare knowledge \r\n• Acquire positive attitude to independent learning  \r\nAll these aspects can be seen in the context of the patient as an individual. Students should be encouraged to return to the ward in private study time to practice clinical skills further.\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n   \r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n   \r\n \r\n', '2018-03-31 12:58:40', 'upload/attachment/4881b78b2e089c44a9f0e0bc96e2917f.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
