endif]--&gt;Feedback form circulated among  participant & post test.<o></o></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;3)<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;Short assessment.<o></o></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Prof Shah Alam<o></o></p>', NULL, '2018-04-09 23:40:04', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (255, 206, 'Workshop on teaching \"Breaking Bad News\" skills  ', 'Workshop is a set of activities designed to promote learning, discussion, and feedback about a topic. It is a brief, intensive course for a small group which emphasizes problem-solving.\r\nPeople Attend Workshops because-\r\n•They provide a high-yield, interactive educational experience on an area of interest.\r\n•Topics are typically applicable to attendee’s professional development or clinical, educational, or research area of interest.\r\n•Their learning format is more efficient, effective, and enjoyable than a large-group lecture or self-directed reading on given subject.\r\n•Allow for networking with colleagues.\r\n\r\nWorkshops serve as an important component to an academician’s teaching portfolio. They provide opportunity to hone teaching skills, establish a national reputation, and find collaborators for other scholarly activities. Once completed, workshops can be used as a springboard for additional scholarly activity.\r\n\r\nA day long workshop on Medical Education for 20 participants-\r\nA)  Pre workshop plan-\r\nStep 1: Choosing a good Topic, Collaborators, and Venue\r\n•Almost any clinical, educational, or research topic can be adapted to a workshop format.\r\n•Presenters should be passionate about topic.\r\n•Topic is timely or potentially controversial.\r\n•Topic aligns with meeting’s educational objectives.\r\n•Workshop provides opportunity for “hands-on” or skill-based practice or learning.\r\n•Must be narrow enough to be covered in appropriate depth within time allotted, often 90 minutes.  \r\n‘Teaching Breaking Bad News Skills’ can be a topic of interest after the aircraft accident in Nepal. Participants may be teachers of Psychiatry faculty from different medical colleges. Venue can be conference hall of IMC.\r\nStep 2: Preparing the Workshop Submission: Structure, Abstract, and defining objectives for the teaching session. Finding out about the audience\r\nStep 3: Planning and Developing the Workshop Presentation. Determine our teaching method and design the appropriate workshop activities.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nB) Schedule for the workshop\r\n\r\n\r\nFlexibility is one of the key ingredients of a successful workshop. As important as it is to plan ahead, it is even more important to be prepared to abandon prepared agenda. We have to-\r\n\r\nIntroduce the group members to the presenters and to each other\r\nOnce the workshop is underway, it is essential to determine who our audience is. It is better to go around the room and ask the group members to briefly introduce themselves and to state their expectations of the session. Finding out who is in our audience will help us strike the appropriate balance and meet the group’s needs and expectations.\r\nOutline the objectives for teaching session\r\nWe have to tell the group what we hope to accomplish in the available time and specify what we will & will not do. Try to match our objectives to the participants’ needs. Feedback on the proposed agenda is helpful in ensuring consensus between our suggested plan and the group’s needs.\r\nCreate a relaxed atmosphere for learning\r\nThe introduction of group members, outlining the workshop objectives and effective questioning & active participation by group members facilitates an atmosphere conducive to teaching and learning.\r\nEncourage active participation and allow for problem solving and/or skill acquisition\r\nParticipation is one key ingredients of a workshop so involving the group in all phases of the session is important. Invite questions, group discussion, and debate. Encourage the participants to learn from each other. If a problem is presented to the group, allow for group solutions.\r\nWhenever possible, limit group size so that active participation will be feasible. Physical arrangements can also facilitate interaction. For example, arrange the chairs so that the participants can all see each other. \r\n\r\n\r\n \r\nFigure 1.  Room layout for an interactive workshop. We can make 4 such arrangements for total 20 participants.\r\n\r\nIn particular, group members could be asked to work through a set of problems or to practice a specific skill. For example, in this workshop on ‘Teaching Breaking Bad News Skills’ we might ask smaller groups of individuals to discuss how they would teach a proper way of breaking bad news to a group of medical students or residents. We might also ask them where this teaching fits into the curriculum and how this skill might best be taught. On the other hand, we might ask the group members to demonstrate the skill on a ‘dummy’ and receive feedback from the group.\r\nProvide relevant and practical information\r\nAlthough active participation and interaction are essential to a successful workshop, the participants must also feel that they have learned something. Workshops are meant to promote the acquisition of new knowledge as well as aptitudes and skills. Some information must, therefore, be provided. Mini-lectures are definitely permissible in a workshop. They often help to set the tone, to cover the basic data, and to ensure a common ground for discussion. Two hours of lecturing in a two hour workshop is, however, not acceptable. Participants should have an opportunity to respond to the presented information. Questions and comments from group participants should also be encouraged.\r\nRemember principles of adult learning\r\nAdults come to learning situations with a variety of motivations and expectations about teaching goals and methods. Moreover, as much of adult learning involves ‘relearning’ rather than new learning, adults often resent the ‘student’ role. Incentives for adult learning usually come from within the person, and feedback is more important than are tests and evaluation. (Knowles, 1978) It is important, therefore, to respect the group’s previous knowledge and experience, their motivation to learn, their potential resistance to change, and their ability to serve as co-learners.\r\nVary your activities and your style\r\nMake sure that the workshop flows at a pace that keeps the participants’ attention. Appropriate pacing implies moving the workshop along while leaving room for the group to slow down or speed up the presentation. \r\nSummarization of the session and request feedback from the group\r\nRestate what we have tried to achieve in the workshop, synthesize the main points made, and discuss plans for follow-up, if appropriate. At times, it is helpful to ask group members to summarize what they have learned during the session. In addition, request feedback from the group as to whether we have accomplished our stated objectives and how to improve the session in the future.\r\nEnjoy ourselves and have fun\r\nIt is important to enjoy what we are doing. If we are enjoying ourselves and are not personally bored with what we are doing chances are that our participants will have a good time and learn something in the process.\r\n\r\n\r\nC) Post workshop evaluation meeting\r\nEvaluation is an integral part of small group teaching. There are two aspects of evaluation- achievement and quality. Informal evaluation can be done for each and every session by asking question to the students as well as by allowing them to ask questions. The formative assessment can be done at the end of the workshop. In addition we can ask participants to complete an evaluation questionnaire consisting of closed and open ended questions. Competent evaluation will always identify the areas for improvement. Reflection should be ongoing and an integral part of any teaching practice including workshop sessions. \r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n1. Ten Simple Rules for Running Interactive Workshops. Pavelin K, Pundir S, Cham J A. PLOS Computational Biology ,www.ploscompbiol.org  February 2014, Volume 10, Issue 2\r\n2. Workshop Preparation and Presentation. AAMC. Carla SpagnolettiM.D., M.S. April 2011.\r\n3. RCPSC \'Twelve Tips for Effective Workshops\' Medical Teacher pp.105-111 by kind permission of Taylor and Francis Ltd. (2000) http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals. \r\n4. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n5. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition.\r\n', '2018-04-07 03:36:56', 'upload/attachment/de827b0faeab476056188da10687bd30.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
