INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (259, 226, 'Interactive large group teaching', 'Answer to question no. 1\r\ni) Lecture is one of the most common forms of instruction in medical education. Lectures can be boring and, worse, useless if they are merely recitation of standard text. There are some approaches to lecturing that makes it more refreshing and useful for students. A lecture is organized in three sections- Introduction, Body and Conclusion. The first 5-10 minutes of the lecture is spent on introduction. Lecturer must attract attention, establish rapport, Identify prior knowledge, provide advance organizer (objectives & key points) & indicate usefulness during introduction. So starting with the definition of burn was not an appropriate approach. Gaining attention of the students should have been the first step to start the lecture.\r\nii) If I am asked to conduct the class on the topic “Burn”, I would have prepared a skeletal hand out of the lecture and provide it to students at the beginning of the class. I would have prepared a power point presentation which starts with a picture of a burn victim of recent days and his/her sufferings in few words and with emotional touch. Then I would have stated the importance of treatment of a burn case that is the usefulness of the lecture, with the objectives of this class. Then I would have identified prior knowledge regarding skin, inflammations and some other related topic. By that time I would have established rapport with my students. This is roughly my plan to begin a class.\r\niii) The Professor could have gained their attention by giving them a short assessment like MCQ, or a short question to answer after discussion with nearby student from their prior knowledge. He could have asked them to mention a recent incidence causing burn injury of many people. He could even show a video clip with instruction on what to look for, to the back benchers. He could have just taken a pause showing a black slide that would have gained their attention. \r\niv) Thought and feeling are inseparable brain processes. This means that information associated with values and feelings will be more readily learned. So even in science disciplines students should be encouraged to develop passionate stances so that they will retain information more efficiently. As burning Rohingya village in Myanmar is a recent and emotionally touchy topic, it was justified to show in slide. Next slide could be on the changes of skin or other damages after burn, which will let them, know the importance & gain their interest of treatment of burn cases properly. So, I would have shown the burning village, followed by a picture of burn victim and telling the story of his/her sufferings in few words. It will make them more attentive for the lecture.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnswer to question no. 2\r\n\r\nLarge group teaching describes the range of methods used to teach large groups usually over 30 or 40 students. The opponents of the large lecture sections argue that large lecture sections dilute the learning process, place an undue burden on faculty in terms of test monitoring, grading, office hours/student interaction, and course management. There is no agreed definition of a large class in the literature, nor should there be. Class size is perceived differently dependent upon the person teaching the course. A large class is one that feels large. Signs that the class is large‘ can be: the class is significantly larger than we are used to and the resources can no longer cope with the number of students if we desire individual attention for the students. Large classes are as effective as small classes when the goals involve learning factual information and comprehending that information. \r\nThe design of an interactive lecture is based on two simple guidelines:\r\n• Break the lecture into segments\r\n• Build-in opportunities for students to actively participate.\r\nHowever ‘Interactive lecture’ can be implemented in a class of 150 students by the team approach to collaborative learning. \r\nTeam structure: In organizing groups, teachers typically do four things:\r\n• They divide a large group, the class into small groups\r\n• They provide a task, usually designed (and, preferably, tested) ahead of time, for the small groups to work on\r\n• They reconvene the larger group into plenary sessions to hear reports from the small groups and negotiate agreement among the group as a whole.\r\n• They evaluate the quality of student work, first as referee, then as judge.\r\n             (Brufee, 1993)\r\n\r\nMcKeachie (1986) uses a buzz group technique to insure student participation in large classes. Dill (1977) describes a technique called ke ts‘ao, or ferment, used in China to get large groups to come to a concensus decision. Think-pair-share first proposed by Lyman in 1981 is another quick and easy method of engaging students in a collaborative activity.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOne minute question/Minute paper/One-minute essay-\r\nOne-minute write activities ask students to stop what they are doing a produce a written response in only one minute. This technique can be used to collect feedback on understanding by asking them to identify what they thought the most confusing point was or to voice a question. It can also allow students an opportunity for immediate application. \r\nWe can ask each student write a very brief paper in which they 1) identify the key points, or 2) summarize the lecture. This activity is effective at the end of a lecture because it gives students a chance to solidify the information while the major points of the lecture are still fresh in their minds. It is also a way of interaction between teacher and student during the class. \r\nWhile concluding the lecture we can review the major points, propose unanswered questions, and create anticipation of the future. We can have them spend two to three minutes at the end of the period writing a summary of main points (the minute paper). As for example we can ask the students to write 3 main points to consider while writing antipsychotic for a particular given patient. We can then discuss one or two of the answers which will make a good interection.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnswer to question no. 3\r\n\r\nWe can start a lecture with a rhetorical question which is a question where no answer is expected. This type of questions can be used to grab the student’s attention.\r\n For example we might start a lecture on treatment-resistant schizophrenia by asking, “How many of you have dealt chronic schizophrenic patient and felt almost hopeless about their prognosis as the patient?” Let us learn something new about Resistant Schizophrenia.\r\n\r\nPerceived dangers cause the brain to downshift to its most rudimentary processing mode and bring learning to a halt.” Negative emotions such as stress or fear impede the brain’s ability to retain or retrieve information. In the classroom, this effect can be seen in overwhelming test anxiety, panic attacks during presentations, or classroom incivility. So, interaction will be hampered if we create a threatening environment if we ask direct recall questions on previous knowledge just at the beginning of the class without any ice breaking or proper introduction.\r\n“You from the 3rd row, tell me the pathological process of developing cerebral edema.” \r\n\r\nReferences-\r\n1. Interactive Large Classes: The Dynamics of Teacher/Student Interaction. Journal of Business & Economics Research Volume 1, Number 8\r\n2. AMEE Medical Education Guide No. 22\r\n3. Making the formal lecture more interactive. Silver I, Rath D. Intercom, volume 15, Number 3, October 2002.\r\n4. The Interactive Lecture An Instructor‚s Manual\r\n5. Making Lectures More Engaging. Michelle Schwartz, Research Associate, for the Learning & Teaching Office, http://www.ryerson.ca/lt/\r\n6. Lecture Strategies That Work. Graduate Teaching & Laboratory Assistants Orientation\r\n            Sponsored  by the Center for Teaching and Learning. http://www.ctl.uga.edu\r\n7. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n8. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition.\r\n', '2018-04-12 04:44:03', 'upload/attachment/04be33f06302285192e872a59edc322e.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
