INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (262, 232, 'Assignment: Unit: Interactive lecture Faculty: Manzare Shamim Assignments : 1. A professor of surgery was giving a lecture on ‘burn’ in an undergraduate medical class. He started with the definition of ‘burn’ using a PowerPoint slide. The students near th', 'Sir,\r\n      Assalamualaikum.  Here I am submitting my assignment as an attachment for your review please.\r\nThanks and Regards.\r\nDr. A.E.MD.ABDUL WASEY', '2018-04-13 10:50:38', 'upload/attachment/78cfac6a19e34427972f47834b0ea160.docx', '<p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed><span lang=\"BN\" xss=removed>Dear fellow. Thanks for your assignments work. Your assignment accepted but following\r\nare my observation. Please relate with your assignment and enrich your\r\nunderstanding. <o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>1.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Assignmen-1:<o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>a.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>There is nothing ‘wrong’ in it, but it is not an\r\ninteresting way of beginning a lecture session. “Gaining attention” is the\r\nfirst step of giving a lecture using Gagne’s principle. Use of ‘trigger\r\nmaterials’ to begin a class is preferred, which may include an <b>anecdote</b>, <b>a picture</b>, <b>a video</b>, a <b>joke,</b> a <b>clinical scenario</b> etc.<o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>b.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Objectives\r\nare  not the starting rather gaining\r\nattention is the 1<sup>st</sup> step of beginning lecture. Starting your class\r\nby use of photograph of a burn victim, or a story from history, personal\r\nexperience, mythology  & relate that\r\nwith burn as a medical topic or you  may\r\nalso ask a relevant question to the students. </span><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>c.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>You are correct by asking question but question should\r\nnot intimidating way<o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>d.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Showing\r\npicture</span><span xss=removed> was OK. Only that relating it in an interesting and meaningful\r\nway to the medical issue of burning should be kept in mind. </span><span xss=removed> </span><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>2.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Your\r\nideas are more or less correct but one minutes question should be like ‘identify\r\nkey points/ summarize topic’.</span><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>3.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Your\r\ndescription is OK.</span><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"yiv1383656007gmail-msolistparagraph\" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Prof\r\nMd Shah Alam</span><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p>', NULL, '2018-04-16 13:12:27', 'F');
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (263, 218, 'Unit: Interactive lecture Faculty: Manzare Shamim Assignments : 1. A professor of surgery was giving a lecture on ‘burn’ in an undergraduate medical class. He started with the definition of ‘burn’ using a PowerPoint slide. The students near the back of th', '1)\r\ni)       There was no wrong in showing the definition of burn in power point slide. But, actually there was wrong in starting of class with showing the definition by using the power point slide. As we know, according to Gagne’s nine events of instruction, the 1st step of starting a class will be, gain attention of the students by asking some questions or by telling stories or showing some pictures or other ice breaking activities that provoke their thoughts and they feel interested and curious about the topic. Gaining attention also make the students to focus their attention to the content. But without doing these, he started his class by showing definition of burn in a power point slide, that made the students uninterested and distracted about the topic also made them absent minded in the class. \r\nHe also did not inform the students about the objectives of the session and did not recall their prior knowledge about burn. He could show the slide of definition during presenting the new content, in the body of the lecture after gaining attention and recalling the prior knowledge of the students. \r\nii)       If I am asked to run the class, at first, I shall try to gain attention of the students by showing a picture of crushed and burned flight or a picture of a building with fire and ask them,\r\n• What you are observing in this picture?\r\n• What will be the probable injuries?\r\n Then I shall inform them about the goals and objectives of the session. Because the students must know what they are going to learn, what they will be able to do at the end of the session, and how they will be able to use the knowledge or skills in the future. \r\nAfter that, I shall try to stimulate recall of prior learning by asking questions like, “what is burn? (not the definition, just to check concept) How it may occur?” and try to relate their prior knowledge with the topic.\r\niii)  .    The professor could have dealt with the situation at the back of the class by showing a picture of crashed aero plane with fire and by asking them about the recent incidence of plane crash and probable injuries of the passengers or to gain their attention instead of using a blank slide and asked the class to volunteer in defining ‘burn’.\r\niv)      Showing the burning village was not ok from my point of view. Showing a picture of burning Rohingya village in Myanmar may divert the students from the topic. There are students of different religions and different background in the class. It may arise racism and political conflict. Some students may feel down and may distract from the topic. This type of photograph may hurt anyone’s religious and political belief.\r\nFollowing things, I shall consider before using a photograph in such a class-\r\n• Is it necessary for the class or not\r\n• It’s advantages and dis advantages\r\n• It should be topic oriented\r\n• It should fulfil my expectations\r\n• It should compel the students to think about it and co relate with the topic\r\n• It should not divert the students from the topic\r\n• It should not arise any political and racial conflict \r\n• It should not violate anyone’s privacy\r\n• It should not criticize any company or organization\r\n• It should not beyond the ethics\r\n\r\n2) Yes, an interactive lecture can be implemented in a class of 150 students.\r\nOne-minute question-\r\nA “one-minute question” may be defined as a very short, in-class writing activity (taking one-minute or less to complete) in response to an instructor-posed question, which prompts students to reflect on the day’s lesson and provides the instructor with useful feedback.\r\n It is commonly used at the end of class to diagnose students’ understanding of key concepts or topics, but can also be used at any point at the middle of lecture.  \r\nOne Minute question can be utilized as an interaction technique in a lecture class in following way-\r\nOne Minute question paper is provided at the middle of lecture at a given point or at the end of the class with the following questions- \r\n • What are the (2-3) most significant things they have learned during the session?\r\n • What is the most confusing concept that has covered in today’s class? \r\nTypically, the One Minute question will ask the students to identify what they found most useful and what they found most challenging to help identify, if further support is needed.\r\nIn this way, we can involve all students in class simultaneously. It ensures equal participation of each and every class member, including anyone who may be too shy or fearful to participate orally. One minute paper can be used to stimulate and facilitate discussion of diversity. It can promote class attendance and attentiveness.\r\nStudent receive full credit for the one minute paper, no matter what they write, because the question does not ask for correct or incorrect answers, instead, it solicits their personal perceptions and experiences.\r\n\r\n3) \r\nOne dialogue that would be helpful in initiating interaction-\r\n  “Good morning! Hope you are well. You are young and energetic. I am watching lots of hope and spirit in your eyes. Mistakes will happen, but mistakes are proof that you are trying. Let’s learn together and do the best we can.”\r\n           \r\n            One dialogue that would hamper interaction-\r\n“Nothing can be happened with you. What is the benefit to teach you? You people are so unmindful and useless!”\r\n', '2018-04-13 09:37:55', 'upload/attachment/a8ffa8ee2973c6a6de03e92dbd2a83a3.doc', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (264, 231, 'A professor of surgery was giving a lecture on ‘burn’ in an undergraduate medical class. He started with the definition of ‘burn’ using a PowerPoint slide. The students near the back of the class seemed uninterested in the topic and were gossiping. The pr', '  Assignment \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCertificate in Medical Education (CMEd)\r\nBIRDEM Academy\r\nModule: Teaching learning \r\nUnit name: Interactive large group teaching\r\n                                                 Code: M3TL3\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n                                                       Submitted by-\r\n                                              Shudhanshu kumar saha\r\n                                         Email- shudhanshukumarsaha@gmail.com\r\n Cell 01759961995\r\n\r\n\r\nComponent of a lecture-\r\n Introduction \r\n Body\r\n Conclusion \r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nThe first 5-10 minutes of the lecture is spent on introduction. At the beginning, the lecturer must attract attention and set the mood of the lecture. This can be done by appropriate use of humor, interesting example etc. It is necessary to establish rapport and provide motivation and enthusiasm to inspire the students to concentrate on the main body of lecture\r\nAn advance organizer provides a statement of the objective of the lecture and at the same time indicates the key points or key feature of the topic.\r\nDuring introduction students pre-existing knowledge base should also be identified. For example, before teaching on burn, short discussion on energy how it produced, source of energy and what is the effect of energy on human body\r\nSo, basic organization of a lecture includes \r\nIntroduction\r\n Attract attention\r\n Establish rapport\r\n Identify prior knowledge\r\n Provide advance organizer(objective and key points) and\r\n Indicate usefulness\r\nBody\r\n Present information\r\n Maintain sequence\r\n Use clear and understandable language\r\n Ask question\r\n Allow student for asking question for clarification\r\nConclusion\r\n Summarize the information keeping the objective and key point in mind\r\n Provide a take home massage\r\n Direct student for future reading\r\n Ask student to write down important points\r\n\r\nAssignment\r\n\r\nA professor of surgery was giving a lecture on ‘burn’ in an undergraduate medical class. He started with the definition of ‘burn’ using a PowerPoint slide. The students near the back of the class seemed uninterested in the topic and were gossiping. The professor tried to attract their attention, but it created uproar in the class itself. To calm the class, he used a blank slide and asked the class to volunteer in defining ‘burn’. It brought a complete silence. Perplexed, he went to his next slide that showed a burning Rohingya village in Myanmar.\r\n \r\nAnswer the following questions considering the above scenario: 4+4+4+ (2+4) =18 \r\ni) Was there anything wrong with showing the definition of the slide? Explain. \r\nBeginning of any teaching-learning session should be with gaining attention of the students/participants and for gaining attention, teacher may ask a question, give a clinical scenario, show a photograph etc. Then, objectives of the session should be stated clearly; so that students can prepare their mind-set. Starting a lecture (large group teaching) by saying “definition of burn” (given scenario) was not a good start, rather it could be better if the lecture would start with a case scenario or story or a question such as, “Did any of you see a burn case?”\r\n\r\nii) If you are asked to run the class, how would you plan to begin? \r\nA lecture on “burn” may be started with a case scenario: A 28-year-old lady was brought to hospital emergency because of scalding pain of feet following accidental fall of boiling water from her hands at kitchen 1-hour ago. Skin of affected areas of feet is red, slightly swollen and very painful to touch. What is the diagnosis?\r\nAnother case scenario may be on burn on “garment factories burn” or “acid violence” may be given. Then the objectives of the session will be presented (definition, types, percentage of burn, complications, treatment etc.) and activation of prior knowledge will be made by asking regarding layers of skin, what is the average surface area of human body etc.\r\n\r\niii) How could the professor have dealt with the situation at the back of the class? \r\nThe professor could gently walk towards the back of the class while talking and express in such a way that it is difficult to listen and see the slides of PowerPoint from the back and encourage students of last one or two rows to come forward. On other wards, he could state that after the first 1 or two slides, there remains a “Quiz” for the students or could say that “burn” is very common and important topic for both “examination” and “clinical practice” or state a story on “burn”.\r\n\r\niv) Was showing the burning village OK? Justify your comment, and outline how you would like to use a photograph in such a class. \r\nI would go against showing such a photograph here. In a lecture for undergraduate class on “burn” one should not use such a photograph, which may have multiple dimensions; political, regional, racial etc. If photographs are to be used in such lectures, burn cases (with prior permission of patients/guardians, if minor) with limited burn of limbs (not face) should be used. Photographs will draw attention because of visual impression, and definitely audio-visual media is better that only lecture (audio).\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2. Can an ‘interactive lecture’ be implemented in a class of 150 students? What is a ‘one-minute question’? Explain with an example how such a question can be utilized as an interaction technique in a lecture class. 2+5+7=14 \r\nInteractive lecture might be implemented in a class for 150 patients if adequate logistic supports are available. Minute paper/mini-minute essays are instructions for students to identify key points or summarization of lectures, usually done towards the end of a lecture. This helps students to solidify information while major points are still fresh in their minds.\r\nIf at the beginning of a class [like acute kidney injury (AKI)], lecturer conveys the message that there will be one minute questions after each segments like criteria for diagnosing AKI (definition), epidemiology, aetiology, clinical presentation, diagnostic work-up, management principles and outcome. There will be 6 different groups (from the whole class) and by lottery one group will be presenting one component (definition, clinical feature, lab. investigation, management principle etc.) and the other groups will be supplementing; thus the whole class is expected to remain attentive and a successful ‘interactive lecture’ is expected at the end.\r\n\r\n3. Create one dialogue that would be helpful in initiating interaction and one that would hamper interaction (in Bangla or in English). 4+4=8\r\nIn a lecture on chikungunya, interaction may be started by asking “how many of you have suffered from chikungunya in 2017 Dhaka outbreak?” Would you please raise your hands? On the other hand if it is asked that “how will you treat a case of chikungunya myocarditis?” \r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-04-14 09:10:01', 'upload/attachment/b8a517d996bb37bfeceda21e245cf0bd.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
