INSERT INTO `assignments_reply` VALUES (271, 222, 'Assignment on TL 3', '1. Discussion on a scenario provided here \r\n\r\nI. There may have something wrong with showing the definition of ‘burn’ in the power point slide, because the students near the back of the class seem uninterested about the topic and were gossiping. The probabilities are: \r\n• Visually poor slide- Type and color of fonts may be inappropriate (too small font size, use of all capitals, sarif font, red text on blue background or vice versa).\r\n• Room environment may lead to poor readability of the slide (light text in well lit room as house lights failed to deem or window blackouts were inadequate for projection to be seen; dark room with dark text).\r\n• Too much text on the slide (due to excessive details).\r\n• Template with distracting items \r\nAs the professors tried to attract their attention, it created uproar in the class itself so there may have other possibilities as well:\r\n• Topic of the day was not appropriate according to the schedule given to the students beforehand.\r\n• Worse still, the professor may have entered into the wrong class.\r\n\r\nII. If I were asked to run the class I would plan to begin in the following ways:\r\n• Having enter into the room I will greet the students and introduce myself, ask questions about the identity of the class and topic of the session. \r\n• Show the picture/photograph of a patient with burn injury as an aid to attract attention.\r\n• Ask them what is the injury and how could it happen to set the mood. \r\n• I will ask to a few of them to share their experience of patients seen with burn injury to establish rapport.\r\n• Motivation and enthusiasm- I will portray the epidemiology of burn situation in Bangladesh and global scenario. \r\n• Identify prior knowledge on the anatomy and functions of the skin, discuss features of dehydration.\r\n• Inform the objectives and the key points.\r\n• Usefulness of the session in reading, assessing and managing patient with burn injury \r\n• I will show my interest and commitment to the topic by being expressive \r\nIII. The professor could have dealt with the situation at the back of the class in the following ways: \r\n• Go to the far end (back) of the class keeping the projector slide on, look at the slide from the back, try to identify anything wrong with the visibility or room environment, if found could apologies and restructure the style immediately and if possible correct the physical environment of the room. \r\n• If no problem is found with the slide, talk to the students whether he is in the right topic in the right class or have the students any problem at the back, if any, that is correctable- manage accordingly; if not correctable immediately- accommodate the back benchers in the front rows.\r\n• If any problem found in the room environment which is not immediately correctable- reschedule the lecture for another day.  \r\nIV. I think showing the burning village was not appropriate with the topic. Because: \r\n• Having little relevance with the topic.\r\n• Rather it could be distracting, divert attention of the students to regional, political and humanitarian issue instead of learning ‘burn’.\r\n• Could lead the students to fall into debate.\r\n• It might be traumatic for some students.\r\nI would like to use a photograph of a patient with non-fatal burn injury having areas of deep and superficial burn to stimulate students’ interest on the following: \r\n• What would be the first-aid measures for this patient\r\n• ABCDE of advanced trauma live support (ATLS)\r\n• Cooling of the burned area \r\n• Fluid resuscitation of this patient \r\n Measurement of the area of the burn\r\n Measurement of body weight\r\n Calculation of the fluid volume\r\n Type of fluid (crystaloid, colloid, blood)\r\n• Associated injuries that may be seen in the photograph to be identified \r\n• Does this patient need admission to the hospital\r\n• Local management of this wound \r\n• Complications that my follow at this particular area of burn and measures to prevent them \r\n\r\n2. Yes, an interactive lecture can be implemented in a class of 150 students.\r\nFollowing measures may be effective: \r\n• Prior to lecture, inform student the topic (class schedule, study guide, website)\r\n• At introduction of the lecture\r\n Gaining attention\r\n Inform what students will be required to learn\r\n How lecture will be related to their reading and practical activities\r\n Breaking the students up into smaller groups to promote discussion of ideas and problem solving during a lecture\r\n Engaging students through clinical cases, ask to work through a case, ask students for inputs during presentation of lecture\r\n• At body of the lecture \r\n Periodic pause and review every 10 to 15 minutes\r\n Questioning to check understanding (rhetorical question, surveys, straight forward question, brain storming, invent examples, compare with another, to consider advantages and disadvantages, strength and weaknesses, produce theory etc.)\r\n Show video clips with instructions on what to look for\r\n Allow to ask questions to clarify \r\n Half-way quizzes, setting questions/problems/task for students to do\r\n Simulation and role plays\r\n Written materials- students are asked to fill in the blanks\r\n• At conclusion towards the end of the class of the lecture, review the key points and ask them to review what they have learnt and share with their neighbors\r\nOne minute question\r\nA one minute question may be defined as a very short in class writing activity, taking one minute or less to complete in response to an instructor posed questions, which prompts students to reflect on the day’s lesson and provides the instructor with useful feedback. This strategy was developed by a physics professor at University of California (1983) and popularized by Cross and Angels (1988) as a quick classroom technique (CATs). It provides the instructors with anonymous feedback on what students are learning in the class.  \r\nIt can also be used: \r\n• As content-centered instructional feedback strategy\r\n• As a student-centered reflection strategy\r\n• To build instructor-student rapport\r\nIt can be given in addition to at the end, at other times during the class period as well, e.g. at the start of the class to activate/turn on ideas and feelings students may already have, right after discussion of a key point to trigger student reflection on that point. \r\nUse of one minute question with examples as an interactive technic in the lecture class  \r\n• Minute paper can improve quality of class discussion by having students write briefly about a concept or issue before they begin discussing it. This gives more reflective students a chance to gather their thoughts prior to verbalizing them and benefits students who are more fearful of public speaking by giving them a script to build on and use as a support structure for communicating their ideas orally.\r\n• An effective way of involving all students in the class simultaneously.\r\n• Ensures equal participation of each and every class member including anyone who may be too shy or fearful to participate orally.\r\n• Each and every student is expected to participate and has something important to contribute. Examples- during this lecture, “what thoughts came to your mind that you did not get the opportunity to share verbally?”\r\n• Can be used to stimulate and facilitate discussions of diversity e.g. interpretation or explanation of differences or similarities or aspects of a topic. \r\n• Can be used to personally validate students as individual if their comments are quoted during the presentation of the lecture. \r\n• Lecturer learn students’ names if students are asked to come up to the front of the room individually to turn in their minute papers and if the students are called by names. \r\n• Serve to build teacher-student rapport if teacher check the minute question, respond personally by writing a comment on it and sign his name below. This communication approximates or simulates that of a personal letter.\r\n\r\n3. Dialogue in initiating and hampering interaction\r\n\r\nI. Dialogue that would be helpful in initiating interaction: \r\n\r\nX said “The girl has pain in right iliac fossa, vomited twice and raised total count of WBC and polymorphs, so it could be a case of Acute Appendicitis.” \r\nY pointed out that, “She has a history of amenorrhea, no history of central abdominal pain at the onset of symptom and looks pale, could it be a case of ruptured ectopic pregnancy?”\r\nZ made a comment, “In that case a blood test for beta HCG can help.”\r\nX pointed out, “Would ultrasonography be a better option?”\r\nWhile Y suggested, “I think a CT scan may be conclusive.”\r\nW supported the suggestion and at the same time reminded, “We should not forget other possibilities to her as well.”\r\n“Considering the financial constraints of the girl, we may wait and watch her for a couple of hours, keeping her on conservative management and review thereafter” P added…………………………\r\n\r\nII. Dialogue that would be helpful in hampering interaction: \r\n\r\nA told, “This middle-aged gentleman has severe upper abdominal pain following a heavy meal, he is habituated to consume alcohol, now have tenderness and rigidity in the upper abdomen, certainly this is case of acute pancreatitis.”\r\nB added, “In that case measurement of serum amylase and lipase will confirm the diagnosis.”\r\nC screamed, “No, no CT scan will be conclusive”\r\nA suggested, “To be in the safe side, he must be managed in the ICU,”…………..\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-04-14 11:41:19', 'upload/attachment/14298c52268ec595a1ca80f6ce903939.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
